# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thomas-nelson-jr
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was born in New Jersey and moved frequently during her childhood before her family settled in Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She earned degrees from the University of Virginia and Purdue University.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] From 2006 to 2014, she was an officer in the Central Intelligence Agency.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] House of Representatives in 2018, unseating incumbent Republican Dave Brat.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was reelected in 2020 and 2022 before leaving Congress to run for governor.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was elected governor of Virginia in 2025, defeating the Republican nominee, Lieutenant Governor Winsome Earle-Sears.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She is Virginia's first female governor.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] As governor, Spanberger signed a controversial "assault weapons" ban, increased the state's minimum wage, vetoed recreational cannabis retail market and collective bargaining legislation, and supported the 2026 Virginia redistricting referendum.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was born Abigail Anne Davis in Red Bank, New Jersey, on August 7, 1979, her father, Martin Davis, a police officer, and her mother, Eileen Davis, a nurse.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She knew from a young age that she wanted to be a spy, writing her diary in code.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her family moved often when she was young, living in Maine, the New York City area, and Philadelphia, before settling in Short Pump, Virginia, when she was 13.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her father had moved from policing to federal law enforcement for the United States Postal Inspection Service.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She graduated from John Randolph Tucker High School and was later a page for U.S. senator Chuck Robb.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger earned a Bachelor of Arts from the University of Virginia in 2001 and a Master of Business Administration from a joint program between the GISMA Business School in Germany and Purdue University's Krannert School of Management.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She initially enrolled at the College of William and Mary before transferring to the University of Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] According to her sister Meredith Schatz, by the time she had completed her undergraduate degree at the University of Virginia, Spanberger was conversationally fluent in Spanish and "five or six more" languages.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In the early 2000s, Spanberger taught English literature as a substitute teacher at the Islamic Saudi Academy in Northern Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She received a conditional job offer from the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) in December 2002.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] While waiting for a background check to be completed, Spanberger worked as a postal inspector, as her father did, focusing on money laundering and narcotics cases.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In July 2006, after Spanberger's background check had been completed, she joined the CIA as a case officer, working to find, recruit, and build relationships with foreign nationals who could have had information of value to the U.S. government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She has publicly said that she gathered intelligence about nuclear proliferation and terrorism.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her first assignment was to Brussels, according to *The Washington Post*.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] During her career, she held, at some point, five different passports, and met people undercover.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In 2014, Spanberger left the CIA and entered the private sector.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was hired by Royall & Company (now a part of EAB) to do consulting work for colleges and universities.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] After the 2016 presidential election, she began working with Emerge America to encourage women to run for state and congressional offices.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In 2017, Virginia governor Terry McAuliffe appointed her to the Virginia Fair Housing Board.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In July 2017, Spanberger announced her candidacy for the United States House of Representatives in Virginia's 7th congressional district in the 2018 election against incumbent Republican Dave Brat, a former Tea Party movement member.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She had begun to consider challenging Brat after attending a town hall meeting he hosted in Nottoway County in February 2017 and made the final decision to run in May after the House voted to repeal the Affordable Care Act, texting her husband, "I'm gonna run and I'm gonna f---ing win".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 12, 2018, Spanberger defeated Dan Ward in the Democratic primary election with 73% of the vote, receiving more votes than any other candidate in the Virginia primaries that day.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In June, after winning the primary, while waiting for a train at the Richmond Staples Mill Road Amtrak station, Spanberger met William C.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Mims, a justice on the Supreme Court of Virginia, who told her he was "impressed with her message".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In August, the Congressional Leadership Fund, a super PAC closely aligned with Republican House Speaker Paul Ryan, conducted a smear campaign against Spanberger.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The campaign, which attempted to tie her to terrorism, was based on an SF-86 application she completed to obtain security clearance, which was released in breach of privacy rules.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In a visit to the district, former Trump adviser Steve Bannon called the race "an absolute bellwether of the entire country" and said that losing it would mean Republican loss of control of the House.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger won the November 6 general election by about 6,800 votes.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Brat won eight of the district's ten counties, but Spanberger dominated the two largest counties, Henrico and Chesterfield, by a combined margin of over 30,000 votes.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] After winning the election, Virginia Supreme Court Justice Mims wrote her a letter extolling the virtues of public service, leadership, and civility, alongside a copy of former Czech President Václav Havel's essay "Politics, Morality, and Civility".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger has said the letter and its impact on her leadership were crucial to her development as a politician.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was the first Democrat to win this seat since 1970, when four-term Democrat John Marsh retired and was succeeded by Republican J.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] But until 1993, the 7th stretched from the outer Washington suburbs through the Shenandoah Valley and Charlottesville to the outer Richmond suburbs; the present 7th is geographically and demographically the successor to what was the 3rd district before 1993.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] That district had been in Republican hands since 1981; former House majority leader Eric Cantor represented it from 2001 until Brat ousted him in the 2014 Republican primary.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger and her colleagues Elissa Slotkin and Mikie Sherrill were described as the "mod squad", a moderate alternative to the progressive "squad".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger and Sherrill shared a Capitol Hill apartment for four years while they served in Congress together.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger faced a close reelection contest against Virginia delegate Nick Freitas, who represented much of the congressional district's northern portion.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She won with 51% of the vote to Freitas's 49%.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Freitas carried eight of the district's ten counties, as Brat had done two years earlier, but Spanberger prevailed by winning the district's shares of Henrico and Chesterfield counties by a combined 43,400 votes, five times her overall margin of 8,400 votes.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was also boosted by Joe Biden narrowly carrying the district; Biden was the first Democrat to win what is now the 7th Congressional District since 1948.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On November 5, days after winning reelection by a margin of 1.8%, Spanberger criticized the Democratic Party's strategy for the 2020 elections in a phone call with other Democratic caucus members that was subsequently leaked.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Calling the elections "a failure" from a congressional standpoint, she singled out Republican attack ads decrying "socialism" and the movement to "defund the police" as prime reasons the Democratic Party lost seats in swing districts.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger argued that Democrats should watch Republican ads before deciding how to talk about issues and never "use the word 'socialist' or 'socialism' ever again".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] After the 2020 elections, Spanberger criticized Democratic messaging, arguing that progressive slogans such as "defund the police" and "socialism" had hurt candidates in swing districts.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] CNN political editor Chris Cillizza called her comments "hard truth" for the Democratic Party, adding that for Democrats to succeed in the 2022 and 2024 elections, they should "listen to the likes of Spanberger" rather than push for "the boldest possible progressive legislation".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] For her first two terms, Spanberger represented a district that stretched from the Richmond suburbs to the fringes of the Shenandoah Valley.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] After the 2020 United States redistricting cycle, Spanberger's district was radically redrawn, and no longer included her home in Henrico County.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She considered not running for reelection in the new district before deciding to do so.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was seen as one of the most vulnerable incumbents of the 2022 election cycle, with pre-election polls projecting a close race with Republican Prince William County supervisor Yesli Vega, a law enforcement officer endorsed by Governor Glenn Youngkin and former president Donald Trump.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger defeated Vega, 52% to 48%, the largest margin at the time in any election Spanberger had run in.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] According to *FiveThirtyEight*'s congressional vote tracker, Spanberger voted with President Trump 8.7% of the time.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In the 2016 presidential election, Trump won 50% of the vote to Hillary Clinton's 44% in Spanberger's future congressional district.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On September 23, 2019, Spanberger joined six other freshman House Democrats with national security backgrounds in calling for an impeachment inquiry into Trump.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger later announced that she would vote in favor of impeachment, saying, "The President's actions violate his oath of office, endanger our national security, and betray the public trust".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 1, 2020, Spanberger tweeted criticism of Trump's reaction to the George Floyd protests, a series of protests against police brutality that began in Minneapolis on May 26.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 2, *The Washington Post* and *The New York Times* quoted Spanberger and several other high-profile former CIA analysts' interpretations of Trump's reaction to the protests as reminiscent of the reaction of totalitarian dictators on the brink of losing control of their dictatorships.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] "As a former CIA officer, I know this playbook, and I know the president's actions are betraying the very foundation of the rule of law he purports to support, the U.S.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger criticized Trump after police used tear gas and rubber bullets on peaceful protestors and a priest during the George Floyd protests to clear a path so that he could have a photo op in front of St.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger opposed Democrats' attempts to amend the Insurrection Act of 1807, saying that amending the rarely used law would not accomplish what Democrats intended.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] According to *PolitiFact*, Spanberger publicly disagreed with some of Biden's immigration policies that have not been subject to congressional votes, but she voted for all 73 bills and resolutions in the House of Representatives that Biden voiced support for.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In December 2023, she was one of six House Democrats to send Biden a letter criticizing Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's Gaza military strategy.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In 2020, during a meeting with then-Governor of Virginia Ralph Northam, Northam suggested she should run for governor someday.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger took his advice, and in November 2023 announced that she would not seek reelection to Congress and would instead run for governor of Virginia in the 2025 election.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She secured the uncontested nomination in April 2025.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In May 2025, while campaigning, Spanberger said she would not sign a bill to fully repeal Virginia's right-to-work law if elected governor.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger is one of the few Virginia gubernatorial candidates to refuse money from Dominion Energy, instead getting donations from the anti-Dominion watchdog Clean Virginia alongside her running mates, who defeated Dominion-backed candidates.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her priorities on immigration include scrapping Youngkin's immigration order allowing local police to help carry out Trump's ICE raids and deportation policy.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She supports rejoining the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative, which Youngkin, a Republican, left after Northam had joined it.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was elected in a landslide, securing 58% of the vote.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Republican nominee, incumbent lieutenant governor Winsome Earle-Sears, received 42%.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] It was the largest margin of victory for a Democratic gubernatorial candidate in Virginia since Albertis Harrison received just under 64% of the vote in 1961.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The official vote margin was over 527,000.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] While Democrats won the three statewide races in Virginia in 2025, Spanberger's 15-point margin of victory was the largest.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger outperformed Kamala Harris in the 2024 presidential election in the state by nearly 10 percentage points, while winning 99% of Harris's voters.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On November 5, Spanberger announced her transition team, which included Chris Lu, Daun Hester, and Yohannes Abraham.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Honorary co-chairs of the team included many Democratic Party of Virginia leaders, such as Louise Lucas, Don Scott, Jennifer Wexton, and Rick Boucher.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger's transition informally began on November 6 with a lunch with Governor Youngkin.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On November 12, Spanberger asked the University of Virginia's board of visitors to pause its search for a new president until her transition was complete, drawing criticism from both Youngkin and conservative alumni of the university for supposed politicization of the board process.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger said Youngkin had done the same during his tenure, and promised structural reform to prevent it.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger made her first cabinet appointment on December 2, announcing Marvin Figueroa as Secretary of Health and Human Resources, and continued to make appointments throughout the month.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was sworn in as governor on January 17, 2026.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was sworn in by former Supreme Court of Virginia Justice William C.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Mims, with her husband Adam holding the Bible and her daughters by her side.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On January 17, 2026, her first day in office, Spanberger signed ten executive orders focusing primarily on affordability, healthcare, housing, education, and preparedness for potential federal policy changes under the Trump administration.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] One of Spanberger's first challenges as governor was managing the January 2026 North American winter storm, responsible for the deaths of four people and hundreds of traffic accidents.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On January 30, Spanberger described the Virginia Leaders in Export Trade (VALET) program, promoting free trade in opposition to Trump's tariffs.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Virginia Port Authority is a major hub of international trade.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On January 19, 2026, Spanberger delivered her first address to a joint session of the Virginia General Assembly, emphasizing affordability, bipartisanship, and pragmatic solutions.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She committed to reentering the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative (RGGI), maintaining Virginia's right-to-work law, collaborating with the federal government where possible, and pushing back against policies harming Virginia jobs or families.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She outlined legislative priorities including lowering healthcare and energy costs, protecting renters, expanding housing production, supporting agriculture amid tariffs, implementing pro-worker measures such as paid family leave and a higher minimum wage, and bipartisan gun safety bills.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Republicans welcomed the calls for unity and right-to-work commitment but proposed alternative tax relief measures and cautioned against increased spending.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger, who campaigned in support of these amendments, said she would campaign for their passage.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] HB736 limits prior authorizations for prescription medication that can lead to costly delays in care.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 30, 2026, the Faith in Housing Act was signed into law.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] It eliminates the rezoning step for faith-based organizations and other tax-exempt nonprofits to develop affordable housing on their properties, allowing religious organizations to give their communities affordable housing with fewer regulatory restrictions.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] SB377 allows utilities to cooperate with high-load energy users to build new substations that exclusively serve them, at the expense of the energy user, to shield other ratepayers from increased costs incurred by their intensive consumption.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger returned the bill to the legislature with amendments on April 13, 2026.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Another amendment removed an exemption for high-load projects approved before July 1, 2026.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The General Assembly accepted these amendments while rejecting a number of other amendments to the bill.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Shortly after taking office in January 2026, Spanberger reiterated a pledge and long-term policy goal of the state Democratic Party to rejoin the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative in her first address to the General Assembly.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 22, to commemorate Earth Day, Spanberger signed an executive order committing Virginia to the United States Climate Alliance, a bipartisan coalition of governors committed to sustaining America's fight against climate change with state-led action.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In May, she signed a slate of legislation aimed at preserving the state's natural resources and treating drinking water for PFAS compounds.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 8, she signed into law HB507, which prohibits the Virginia Department of Environmental Quality from issuing air permits to data centers with backup diesel gen-sets that do not satisfy the Environmental Protection Agency's tier 4 emission standards.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] During her campaign, Spanberger committed to expanding the state's solar and wind energy capacity.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On March 25, Spanberger created the cabinet-level position of Chief Energy Officer via executive order, appointing Southern Environmental Law Center attorney Josephus Allmond to the position.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The office is tasked with cooperating with the Virginia Secretary of Commerce and Trade, the Virginia Department of Energy, PJM Interconnection, and energy utility providers to address rising energy costs, expand clean energy generation, and develop a statewide energy strategy.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She later signed HB1444, formally codifying the Clean Energy Innovation Bank that had been trialed by the Virginia Department of Energy in 2024, which financed clean energy projects, greenhouse gas emissions reduction projects, and other similar projects.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The recission order does not force local departments to exit existing agreements with ICE.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Nevertheless, the order has been criticized by Republicans and ICE officials, who have called it a "sanctuary state" policy that has led to an increase in immigrant crime.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] At the same time, she vetoed a law that would have prevented ICE from conducting civil arrests at courthouses, schools, and healthcare facilities.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Virginia House of Delegates voted to approve an amendment enshrining abortion access for all Virginia citizens shortly before Spanberger took office.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Senate followed suit shortly thereafter.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger signed the bill and sent it to the voters for final approval on February 6, 2026.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 8, Spanberger signed the Right to Contraception Act, enshrining Virginians' right to obtain and use contraceptive drugs or devices and healthcare providers' right to provide them.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 6, 2026, Spanberger signed into law HB1, which would increase the state's hourly minimum wage from $12.77 to $13.75 by January 1, 2027, and $15 by 2028; thereafter the minimum wage will be indexed to increases in the consumer price index and hiked incrementally every year.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Two days later, she signed HB20, which rescinded a statutory exemption from the state minimum wage law for farm laborers and employees, which would go into effect on January 1, 2027.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On May 11, 2026, Spanberger signed a bill establishing a Paid Family and Medical Leave Insurance program administered by the Virginia Employment Commission, set to go into effect in 2028.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The program will be funded by a trust fund financed by remittances from employers deducted from employee payrolls and, for employers of more than ten workers, employer contributions.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The law extends benefits to over 1.2 million uncovered workers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 22, she signed the Equal Pay Act, which prohibits employers from querying prospective workers about their pay history and using that data in considering whether to hire them or in determining their salary unless they voluntarily provide their pay history.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She also signed a bill that expands legal protections against wage theft.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 26, 2026, Spanberger signed legislation hiking benefits for unemployment claims filed after July 5 of that year by 11.2%, from $430 to $478 per week.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On May 14, 2026, Spanberger vetoed SB378 and HB1263, collective bargaining legislation backed by the Virginia Service Employees International Union (SEIU) and various labor groups.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] HB542 was the state legislature's most recent effort to expand the commercial sale of recreational cannabis.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] It would have established a framework for the creation of a cannabis retail market administered and regulated by the Virginia Cannabis Control Authority and partially liberalized certain restrictions on sales quantities.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The General Assembly rejected these recommendations.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] As a result, Spanberger vetoed the bill on May 19, 2026, despite supporting the creation of a retail cannabis market as long as it had strong labeling and regulation.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She cited the bill's "rushed timeframe", which she said gave the state too little time to design comprehensive strategies for regulating the market or to learn from the successes and errors of other states that liberalized cannabis retailing.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Negotiations continued in the following weeks, and they reached a compromise on June 16.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Semi-automatic shotguns for hunting are not considered assault weapons, and semi-automatic firearms owned before July 1 may be retained.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The law was subject to litigation immediately after being enacted.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] She signed other restrictions relating to the possession of firearms in hospitals, the presence of polling places, and laws relating to gun owners' responsibility to keep their firearms secure.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Bypassing the commission would require another amendment to the Constitution of Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The General Assembly can pass amendments through a majority vote by the House of Delegates and the Senate in two consecutive legislative sessions, which would send the amendment to be approved by the voters as a ballot measure.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] A corresponding resolution was adopted by the Assembly in October that allows the Virginia General Assembly to consider constitutional amendments related to redistricting during a special session, which was agreed to by the House on the 29th and by the Senate on the 31st.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Both floors reapproved the amendment after the beginning of 164th General Assembly, and Spanberger signed the legislation that sent it to the voters.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The amendment was ultimately approved, 51.69% to 48.31%.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] It was struck down by the Supreme Court of Virginia on May 8, a ruling appealed by state Democrats.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Supreme Court rejected the appeal on May 15.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] On February 24, 2026, Spanberger delivered the Democratic response to Trump's 2026 State of the Union Address from the chamber of the House of Burgesses in the reconstructed Capitol in Williamsburg, Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Hodges* is overturned, and the Voting Rights Restoration Amendment, which restores voting rights to formerly incarcerated people who completed felony sentences.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] The 2026 legislative session concluded on March 14 with sine die adjournment without a final biennial budget agreement, due to a dispute over data center tax exemptions.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In April 2026, Spanberger signed a bill that eliminates tax breaks for organizations related to the Confederate States of America, and a package of legislation relating to maternal healthcare and telemedicine.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Most bills would take effect on July 1, 2026.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Very early in Spanberger's governorship, opinion polls showed that her job approval rating was fairly stable and similar to the average of previous Virginia governors.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] A poll by the Institute for Policy and Opinion Research at Roanoke College in early February showed that 53% of Virginians gave her high marks for her job performance, while 38% disapproved.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] By April, her approval rating had dropped significantly, with a *Washington Post*–Schar School poll finding that 47% of voters approved of Spanberger and 46% disapproved.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] This marked the worst net approval rating for a governor in the early months of their term in *Washington Post* polls since the early 1990s.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] Similarly, a State Navigate poll conducted on April 10–13 showed her net approval rating to be breaking even.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] But after the 2026 Virginia redistricting amendment, a *Public Sentiment Institute* poll found that 52% of voters approved of Spanberger and 41% disapproved, as in earlier polls.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p01] In June 2026, *Vox* described Spanberger as polarizing, attempting to placate both businesses and Democrats, while being viewed negatively by Republicans.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger positions herself as a moderate Democrat and has called herself a "passionate pragmatist".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In the 2019 speaker of the United States House of Representatives election on the opening day of the 116th United States Congress, Spanberger voted for Representative Cheri Bustos, an Illinois Democrat, joining 11 other Democrats who did not back Nancy Pelosi.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, overturning the right to abortion established by *Roe v.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Wade*, saying that "it undermines the right to privacy and a woman's right to choose".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] She opposes legislation to restrict abortion, saying that the government should not "mandate a pregnancy".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] During her gubernatorial campaign, Spanberger said she would support a constitutional amendment to restore "the *Roe* standard" and that she supported Virginia's existing laws requiring minors seeking abortions to receive parental consent, and certain limitations on third-trimester abortions.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In February 2023, Spanberger was one of 12 House Democrats who voted in favor of H.J.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] 7, a Republican-sponsored resolution to terminate the national emergency concerning COVID-19 declared in March 2020.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] During her 2025 campaign for governor of Virginia, a January 6, 2021, photograph of Spanberger wearing an emergency escape hood inside the Capitol was circulated online by critics, who misrepresented it as COVID-19 protective gear and mocked her.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In 2023, Spanberger voted against overturning the District of Columbia's revision of its criminal code, which reduced the maximum penalties for burglary, carjacking, and robbery.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger opposes defunding the police, and has supported bills that would increase the ability of local police departments to hire and train more officers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Although she was not a member of Congress when it passed, Spanberger criticized the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act supported by President Donald Trump, arguing that its permanent tax cuts for corporations would increase the national debt.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger called for the passage of the USMCA trade deal negotiated by the Trump administration, Mexico, and Canada.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger opposed Trump's tariffs during her 2025 gubernatorial campaign.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] She has promoted free trade during her tenure as governor.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In May 2020, Spanberger voted against the HEROES Act, a proposed $3 trillion stimulus package in response to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] She said the bill went "far beyond" pandemic relief and had no chance of passing the Republican-controlled Senate.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In November 2020, Spanberger led a bipartisan effort to secure the 340B Drug Pricing Program against changes that would lead to significant increases in prescription medication costs.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger supports banning members of Congress from trading stocks.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] She has introduced legislation that would require lawmakers, as well as their spouses and dependent children, to place assets in a blind trust while in office.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In September 2025, Spanberger wrote an opinion article in *The Washington Post* opposing DOGE for conducting mass layoffs of federal workers in 2025 which particularly affect Virginia, as many federal workers live there.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger focused her 2025 gubernatorial campaign on affordability and jobs.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Through her "Strengthening Virginia Schools Plan", Spanberger announced she would make higher education more affordable and accessible and make it easier for high school students to take college-level courses.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] She supports allowing teachers to deliver instruction and manage curriculum without interference from political bodies or agendas.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger has emphasized strengthening public schools by hiring and fairly compensating teachers, rather than supporting private schools and school choice.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger has called climate change "one of the greatest and most imminent threats to our economy, our national security, and our way of life" and said she will "stand up to attacks against science".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] During a 2019 Committee on Foreign Affairs meeting, she asked the Trump administration to reverse its isolationist policies, saying, "it's in our national interest to reinforce our stature as a global leader on international environmental and energy issues".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger called the Green New Deal proposed by Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez a "bold compilation of ideas meant to address global climate change" but criticized it for allegedly including unrelated policy proposals and not identifying specific resolutions to the problems that it identifies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] "Overall I am not a supporter of the Green New Deal", she said.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In February 2023, during the Russo–Ukrainian War, Spanberger signed a letter advocating that President Biden give Ukraine F-16 fighter jets.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In June 2025, Spanberger supported the U.S. strikes on Iranian nuclear sites.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger has called for a new version of the Federal Assault Weapons Ban that expired in 2004.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] She favors requiring background checks on private gun sales and supported a ban on bump stocks.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Before she served in Congress, Spanberger volunteered with Moms Demand Action, a gun-control advocacy group.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger supports the Affordable Care Act (Obamacare).
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] She supports a public option for healthcare via the proposed Medicare-X Choice Act.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In November 2020, she called reducing the cost of prescription drugs "the top priority of families in my district".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In January 2020, Spanberger sponsored the Public Disclosure of Drug Discounts Act, which passed the House unanimously.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] The bill requires pharmacy benefit managers (PBMs), who manage prescription drug benefits for health insurance companies, to publicize the rebates, discounts, and price concessions they negotiate, via a website hosted by the U.S. secretary of health and human services.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger also co-sponsored the Elijah Cummings Lower Drug Costs Now Act, which grants Medicare Part D the power to negotiate prescription prices directly with drug companies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger objected to President Trump's travel bans from certain predominantly Muslim countries and argued that they would aid jihadist propaganda by allowing a portrayal of the U.S. as an anti-Muslim country.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] She has voiced her support for stronger border security measures but opposes Trump's proposed wall.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger voted for a bill that included funding for border infrastructure, technology at ports of entry, and more customs and border protection officers and agents.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] She said she does not support "sanctuary cities" but also called the term "a campaign slogan a lot of people get caught up in".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] She added that it "degrades the value of the conversation if we're not actually talking about what the real concern is." Spanberger called for a pathway to legal status for illegal immigrants who abide by the laws, work, and pay taxes.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Immigration and Customs Enforcement to be notified when undocumented immigrants attempt to purchase firearms.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In 2022, she voted in favor of the Respect for Marriage Act.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] When Spanberger ran for governor in 2025, she was endorsed by the Human Rights Campaign, an LGBTQ advocacy group.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In April 2006 she married Adam Spanberger, a University of Virginia-trained engineer, and her high school sweetheart.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] She helped run a Girl Scouts troop for her daughters when they were young.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] In 2014, the family moved to Henrico County.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] Before Spanberger became governor, they lived in Glen Allen, Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abigail-spanberger-p02] During her time in Congress, Spanberger roomed with colleague Mikie Sherrill, who was elected governor of New Jersey on the same day Spanberger was elected governor of Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Clark was born in Elizabethtown in the Province of New Jersey.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] His father, Thomas Clark, realized that he had a natural grasp for math so he hired a tutor to teach Abraham surveying.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] While working as a surveyor, he taught himself law and went into practice.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] He became quite popular and became known as "the poor man's councilor" as he offered to defend poor men who could not afford a lawyer.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Clark married Sarah Hatfield circa 1749, with whom he had 10 children.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] While she raised the children on their farm, Clark was able to enter politics as a clerk of the Provincial Assembly.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Later he became high sheriff of Essex County and in 1775 was elected to the Provincial Congress.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] He was a member of the Committee of Public Safety.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Early in 1776, the New Jersey delegation to the Continental Congress was opposed to independence from Great Britain.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] As the issue heated up, the state convention replaced all their delegates with those favoring the separation.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Because Clark was highly vocal on his opinion that the colonies should have their independence, on June 21, 1776, they appointed him, along with John Hart, Francis Hopkinson, Richard Stockton, and John Witherspoon as new delegates.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] They arrived in Philadelphia on June 28, 1776, and voted for the Declaration of Independence in early July.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] During the events of the Revolutionary War, Clark remained in the Continental Congress through 1778, when he was elected as Essex County's Member of the New Jersey Legislative Council.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] At one point his two sons were captured by the British and incarcerated on the prison ship HMS Jersey, as they were enlisted soldiers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Later, New Jersey returned him twice more, from 1780 to 1783 and from 1786 to 1788.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Clark was one of New Jersey's three representatives at the aborted Annapolis Convention of 1786, along with William C.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] In an October 12, 1804 letter to Noah Webster, James Madison recalled that Clark was the delegate who formally motioned for the Constitutional Convention, because New Jersey's instructions allowed for consideration of non-commercial matters.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Clark, more than many of his contemporaries, was a proponent of democracy and the common man, supporting especially the societal roles of farmers and mechanics.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Because of their emphasis on production, Clark saw these occupations as the lifeblood of a virtuous society, and he decried the creditor status of more elite men, usually lawyers, ministers, physicians, and merchants, as an aristocratic threat to the future of republican government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Unlike many Founding Fathers who demanded deference to elected officials, Clark encouraged constituents to petition their representatives when they deemed change necessary.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] In May 1786, Clark, aided by thousands of petitions in the preceding months, pushed a pro-debtor paper money bill through the New Jersey legislature.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Senate in 1788, but was later elected to the House in 1791, where he served until his death.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Clark retired before the state's Constitutional Convention in 1794.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Clark Township in Union County, New Jersey, is named for him, as is Abraham Clark High School in Roselle, New Jersey.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/abraham-clark] Clark is buried there at the Rahway Cemetery in Rahway, New Jersey.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Harrison is the first governor of Virginia to have been born in the 20th century.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Harrison was born in Alberta, Virginia, the son of Albertis Sydney Harrison and Lizzie, (née Goodrich).
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] He has been widely reported as related to Benjamin Harrison V who signed the Declaration of Independence and two United States presidents, William Henry Harrison and Benjamin Harrison, the 9th and 23rd Presidents, however before his death, he found this to be false.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] He received a Bachelor of Laws degree from the University of Virginia Law School in 1928.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Harrison married Lacey Virginia Barkley in 1930.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] They had two children: Antoinette H Jamison and Albertis S.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Harrison III; and 6 grandchildren: Joseph D.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Goodrich Harrison, Monica Harrison Kopf, Virginia Lacey Jamison, and James Carper Jamison II.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Harrison went into legal practice in Lawrenceville, Virginia, where he became town attorney, before being elected commonwealth's attorney of Brunswick County.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] He was elected to the Senate of Virginia in 1947.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] He served there for ten years, before being elected Attorney General of Virginia in 1957.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Harrison resigned as attorney general in April 1961 to run for governor, winning election that November with 63.84% of the vote, defeating Republican H.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] His administration increased educational financing for new schools and laboratories and raised teachers' pay.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] He promoted the development of state-supported colleges and technical schools as well as improved vocational training.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] He helped to modernize state banking laws to attract investment and accelerated highway construction.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] He sat on the Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals, later renamed the Supreme Court of Virginia, from 1968 to 1981.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] In 1968 he chaired the Commission on Constitutional Revision that drafted the 1971 Constitution of Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] As Attorney General, Harrison was responsible for defending the state's resistance to school integration, as part of the Massive Resistance strategy endorsed and led by the state's political leader, United States Senator Harry F.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Part of Massive Resistance involved the closing of public schools in various Virginia cities and counties to prevent racially integrated classrooms.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] County School Board of Prince Edward County* (1952) was one of the companion cases to *Brown v.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Board of Education* (1954), but the Supreme Court had left enforcement to the local federal district judge.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Moreover, the Gray Commission of Byrd loyalists had recommended passage of various laws to avoid or delay integration.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] After opinions by the Virginia Supreme Court on January 19, 1959, as well as a three-judge federal panel overturned much of the new Virginia legislation, Governor J.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Lindsay Almond (previously attorney general) and Harrison decided not to defy those courts and allowed schools in Arlington and Norfolk to reopen.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] However the schools in Prince Edward County closed in 1958 and did not reopen until 1963, as white students used tuition grants to attend a private segregation academy at state expense, while black students were left to volunteer efforts.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Other problematic school closures, ultimately opened pursuant to federal court orders included those in Albemarle, Warren County and later New Kent County (the subject of the 1968 Supreme Court decision in *Green v.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] County School Board of New Kent County* (1968).
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Harrison told the board to comply unless they were willing to risk prosecution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] By this time, he, like a number of other Byrd Democrats, had concluded that obstinate resistance to integration could not continue.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Another aspect of Massive Resistance involved new laws regulating attorney ethics, designed to attack practices of the NAACP, which was pursuing the desegregation actions.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Supreme Court deferred to an upcoming decision of the Virginia Supreme Court about those new ethics rules in *Harrison v.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] NAACP* (1959), but the case came before it twice more in *NAACP v.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Button* (1963) (which was reargued after Harrison resigned as attorney general to run for governor, and which Virginia lost under attorney general Robert Young Button.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] Harrison died of a heart attack at his home in Lawrenceville on January 23, 1995.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] He is buried in Oakwood Cemetery in Lawrenceville, Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/albertis-harrison] The courthouse in Lawrenceville is named in his honor.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Major-General **Alexander Spotswood** (12 December 1676 – 7 June 1740) was a British army officer, explorer and colonial administrator who served as the governor of Virginia from 1710 to 1722.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] After an unsatisfactory military career, in 1710 he was appointed as Virginia's governor, a post he held for twelve years.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During that period, Spotswood engaged in the exploration of the territories beyond the western border, of which he was the first to see the economic potentials.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] As the governor of Virginia, Spotswood's first preoccupation was to make sea routes safe and fight against the pirates.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] After a long effort, the famous pirate Blackbeard was hunted down and killed in 1718.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In addition, Spotswood promoted the economic growth of the colony by founding the metallurgical settlements of Germanna; introduced the juridical instrument of habeas corpus; and introduced the rules for the commercial relations with Native Americans and those for the tobacco export trade.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] His tenure was characterised by a growing conflict with the Virginian political classes, which ended with his removal from office.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Years later, between 1730 and 1739, Spotswood was the Deputy Postmaster General of British America and, with his young friend Benjamin Franklin, extended the postal service network north of Williamsburg and improved its efficiency.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] At the outbreak of the War of Jenkins' Ear, Spotswood was called back into army service.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Promoted to major general, he was put in command of the colonial troops stationed in America with the task of preparing a military action against the Spanish stronghold of Cartagena de Indias, but, in Annapolis, where he was to consult with the local governors, he died suddenly in 1740.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Alexander Spotswood was born in Tangier, a city on the African shore of the Strait of Gibraltar, in 1676.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] 1638 – December 1709), the daughter of the Rev.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] 1655), who gave him an only son, Alexander.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Alexander's older half-brother (by his mother's first marriage to George Elliott) was Roger Elliott, who became one of the first governors of Gibraltar.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Both parents had Scottish origins, and the father, although economically ruined, could boast an illustrious lineage as a direct descendant of Robert the Bruce.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] His family had ancient baronial origins and had enjoyed great prestige until the time of the English Revolution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] There had been illustrious Spotswoods, such as judge Sir Robert Spottiswoode (Alexander's grandfather) and Archbishop John Spottiswoode.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In 1684, following attacks of native Berber troops under the guide of governor Ali ben Abdallah, the city of Tangier was evacuated and the Spotswood family returned to England, where the father died in 1688.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In May 1693, at the age of sixteen, Spotswood enlisted in the English Army, the army of the Kingdom of England, with the rank of Ensign in the Earl of Bath's Regiment of Foot.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] He served first in Ireland and then in the Flanders.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Over the years, distinguishing himself for skill, courage and intelligence, he climbed the military hierarchy to the rank of lieutenant colonel.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The War of Spanish Succession broke out in 1701.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The main European powers fought each other throughout the following decade.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough, was in command of the English army stationed in central Europe.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Alexander Spotswood was part of it as deputy quartermaster general.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The troops remained quartered along the River Rhine for three years for the protection of the Netherlands.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Marlborough's army descended into Bavaria In 1704, taking the Franco-Bavarian forces by surprise.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The Battle of Blenheim took place on August 13 and ended in a major British victory.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During the battle Spotswood was severely wounded in the chest during a heavy artillery attack.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Medicated on the battlefield, he was then sent to London to convalesce.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] He survived and kept the cannonball, which he used to show his friends and guests.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] He returned to the Flanders almost two years later.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] On 11 July 1708 he fought in the Battle of Oudenaarde, in the Netherlands, where his horse was killed and he fell prisoner to the French troops.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] But Duke of Marlborough, once again the winner of the battle, obtained his release by negotiating personally with the enemy, and Spotswood returned to his duties as quartermaster general to oversee the corn supply for the troops.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] However, his disappointment for the slowdown of his military career was growing.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Despite the good relationship with and the trust of his superiors, he was stuck in the rank of lieutenant colonel.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] His ambitions, fuelled by the many but never kept promises of promotion, were continuously frustrated.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In September 1709, having spent half of his life in the army, he took his leave and returned to London.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During the war, Spotswood had made good friends not only with the Duke of Marlborough, but also with another of his commanders, George Hamilton, 1st Earl of Orkney.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Hamilton had held the post of governor of the colony of Virginia from 1704, but resided in London and was represented on American soil by a plenipotentiary delegate, with a nominal mandate as deputy governor.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In 1707 the deputy governor, Robert Hunter, had been captured by the French at sea and the colony was thus temporarily administered by a local government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] At the suggestion of Hamilton himself, with perhaps an additional push by Marlborough, on February 18, 1710 Queen Anne appointed Spotswood as vice governor of Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] On April 3, Spotswood left for the Americas from the port of Spithead, in southern England, aboard the man-of-war HMS *Deptford*, in convoy with other British ships to ward off pirate attacks.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] At the beginning of the eighteenth century, Virginia was the most prosperous and populous of the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The inhabitants numbered around 80,000, including 20,000 slaves – most of them from the Bight of Biafra – employed in the vast tobacco plantations, at the service of a confederation of landowners.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The export of tobacco was still one of the most lucrative activities, but in recent times, due to the war against the French and the consequent closure of the Atlantic trade routes, it was not as rewarding as in the past, and overproduction had caused prices to drop.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In addition, in a period considered the golden age of piracy, the southern waters of British America were swarming with pirates and corsairs.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Coming from the Caribbean Sea, they sailed northwards along the American coastline as far as Virginia, making harmful raids.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Moreover, the land borders of the colony were at that time threatened by the original inhabitants of numerous Native American tribes.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] After ten weeks of good navigation, the convoy arrived in Virginia on June 20, and landed at the Hampton Roads bay (then known as *Kecoughtan*, the local Algonquian name).
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Three days later, Spotswood was in Williamsburg, the capital of the colony, where he was sworn in as governor, in the newly built Capitol.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] For the previous four years the colony had been ruled by the twelve members of the Governor's Council, who were appointed by the King.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Just like the fifty representatives of the House of Burgesses (who were elected by their Virginian peers), they belonged to the class of the great landowners whose real aim was to establish a *de facto* oligarchy.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Their interests often clashed with those of the Crown, and in the oversea territories their interests generally prevailed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] On July 5 Spotswood made his first encounter with this problem.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] A resolution passed by the Governor's Council prior to his arrival had abolished the application of the annual payments for the tobacco lease and established the principle that tobacco be exchanged at a public sale.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Now, considering the low revenues, the Crown had decided to return to the old method of trade, but the Governor's Council, whose members controlled the public sale of tobacco, refused to implement the new rule.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood favoured the council's opinion, and this was the first public conflict of interests between the Crown, of which Spotswood would be for years to come a staunch supporter, and the wishes of the local ruling classes.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In addition, following the Crown's suggestions, he proposed to rebuild the College of William & Mary which had been destroyed by a fire five years earlier, and to establish a court of *oyer and terminer* (a sort of superior criminal court) that would have to meet every six months.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Meanwhile, another pressing issue reawakened his military vocation.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] A colonial militia of about 15,000 men was deployed to protect the land borders.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The majority of the troop came from the lower labouring classes, were poorly armed and operated under the orders of inexperienced commanders.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Since his arrival in Virginia, Spotswood had shown concern about the colony's vulnerability and had started to reorganise and strengthen the militia to match the task of defending the colony.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During the summer of 1711, he personally supervised the installation of a series of cannons in the ports between Yorktown and Jamestown to prevent a possible French naval invasion.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] That was the beginning of the so-called Tuscarora War.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood, well aware that it was a real war, considering how badly equipped the militia was, requested weapons and ammunition from England, which however would take a few months to arrive.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] His aim being to prevent other tribes from joining the Tuscarora revolt, he headed south with the 15,000 militia men and stopped on the bank of the Nottoway River.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The local tribes proved to be well disposed towards the British and offered them military support against the Tuscarora.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] As a guarantee, Spotswood demanded that each tribe deliver two of the young sons of the tribal chiefs as hostages, to be educated in Williamsburg at the College of William & Mary.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The objective was twofold: to give them a Christian education, so that they could return later as missionaries to their own tribes – within the framework of a wider operation to civilise the Indians –, and at the same time to guarantee for a certain period of time the friendship of those tribes.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In early December, hostages from several tribes arrived in Williamsburg.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The House of Burgesses, however, was not happy about this resolution, as they would have liked a more direct military action against the Indians.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Between the summer and the fall of the following year, some of the rebel Tuscarora chiefs were captured and transferred to North Carolina for trial.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The War of Spanish Succession ended in April 1713, and the British victory led to the reopening of the Atlantic trade routes and the annexation of new colonies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The Virginian economy was revitalised, and in particular the tobacco export trade which in recent years had been severely affected by the conflict.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Tobacco in those days was also used as a means of payment and was sold by the weight.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] To make more profit traders often added poor quality to high-quality varieties, causing prices to drop.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Previous colonial governments had made attempts on several occasions to regulate the trade, but nothing had ever really come of it.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] So, in November 1713, Spotswood, to bring the tobacco market under control and set limits to the practices of the big landowners, submitted to the House of Burgesses the *Tobacco Inspection Act*.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The new law, supported by the Governor's Council, required tobacco to be inspected before shipment to Europe.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In Spotswood's intentions there would thus be a reduction in the quantities exported, resulting in an increase in the quality of the goods and a consequent increase in demand and in price.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] To soften the opposition of the House of Burgesses', Spotswood appointed as inspectors some of the representatives in favour of his proposal, which was finally approved.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The reform, however, produced only partial results compared with the expectations: prices did not rise immediately, and the inspection procedure was disliked by the landowners.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Yet another initiative by Spotswood caused him to lose the favour of the Virginian elite.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In December 1714, he had the *Indian Trade Act* passed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] All commercial activities with the Indians south of the James River were placed under the exclusive control of the Virginia Indian Company, established with an allocation of £10,000.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The measure should have put an end to the illegal trade that took place along the border and which, according to Spotswood, was one of the reasons for the unrest of the Indians, and at the same time was against the interests of the colonials who were trading privately with the Indian tribes.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] William Byrd II, an influential member of the Governor's Council who wanted Spotswood's position for himself, was in control of much of the trade with the Indians, particularly the Cherokee, to whom he sold cloth and weapons.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Shortly after the law was passed, Byrd left for England on personal business, but certainly also with the intention of bringing Spotswood discredit in the various branches of the royal administration.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The disputes between Spotswood and the members of the House of Burgesses grew until they degenerated in 1715.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During an assembly held between August and September the representatives, instead of concentrating on the problems of the colony's defence as was Spotswood's recommendation, challenged the *Indian Trade Act* and the *Tobacco Inspection Act*.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The discontent generated by the latter among landowners and merchants had played a fundamental role in the last elections of the House of Burgesses.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Almost all the representatives who had previously supported the act had lost their seat, and a large section of the newly elected were in disagreement.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The scarce rainfall of the previous year had provided the tobacco traders with reasons to justify the request of being allowed to sell all the tobacco produced, regardless of its quality, ignoring therefore the provisions of the *Tobacco Inspection Act*.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] After five weeks of time-wasting discussions – which irritated him all the more now that some Indian tribes at the border were becoming hostile, putting the application of the *Indian Trade Act* at risk –, Spotswood put an end to the debates and closed the assembly.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In early 1716, an anonymous letter from Virginia to the London Board of Trade denounced Spotswood for alleged violations of the law, even more strongly than previous still anonymous letters, and accused him of greed and tyranny.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Despite the contrasts with the House of Burgesses, during the middle years of his tenure, Spotswood concentrated mainly on the exploration beyond the western frontier, beyond the foothills of Piedmont.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] On account of the Tuscarora war, the situation at the border had become tense again, but after one hundred years of periods of war followed by periods of peace, the British and the Indians had learned that, in the absence of a winner, they had better try and live together.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] To deal with the Indian threat, since his arrival in Virginia Spotswood had sent rangers to patrol the border and explorers in search of a pass through the Blue Ridge Mountains.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In the spring of 1714, he personally joined an expedition to explore the upper reaches of the York and Mattaponi Rivers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] These explorations took place for precise strategic purposes.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In the summer of 1714, having sufficiently secured the borders, Spotswood went into action by establishing two forest settlements beyond the Tidewater border, which for the past century had signed the limit of British expansion.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The first settlement, Fort Christanna, stood on the southern bank of the Meherrin River, near the border with North Carolina.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Built for the headquarters of the Virginia Indian Company, the company created under the *Indian Trade Act*, the fort housed a school for the education of Indians to the Christian way of life.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood's objectives, in addition to those of immediate strategic utility already pursued at the time of the Tuscarora war, were ambitious: to turn the traditionally semi-nomadic Indians into a resident population.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The second settlement established by Spotswood was Germanna, situated north of a bend of the Rapidan River.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] A group of refugees from the Palatinate, arrived in America in 1709 with the approval of Queen Anne following the destruction of their lands during the War of Spanish Succession, had settled in the region and they had discovered deposits of silver and iron.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Initially, nine families of German Protestants settled in Germanna, working for the local smelting furnaces.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In October 1714, news came that Queen Anne had died in early August.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] 1716 saw the results of the previous explorations in the western territories.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] On June 12, Spotswood reported to the Governor's Council that some rangers had found a passage through the mountains and offered himself to lead an expedition beyond Piedmont, in regions then unknown.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The Council approved the proposal, on the consideration of its commercial and strategic potential.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood left Williamsburg with a few men on August 20, 1716, and headed for Germanna, where a meeting point had been fixed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Here the expeditionary force was formed, and on 29 August a group of sixty-three men set off for the mountains.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The group included influential members of the settlers' community, servants, rangers, native guides and a good number of horses and dogs.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The group went up the Rapidan River, hunting animals and toasting the new king, through a dense bushy area crossed by numerous water streams.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During the march, some men contracted measles and were left behind in a field hospital readily set up and manned by rangers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The rest of the group proceeded under the threats of bears and rattlesnakes, until they reached the source of the Rapidan River on the Blue Ridge Mountains, on 5 September.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] They crossed the mountains passing through a gorge by the name of Swift Run Gap at an altitude of 720 m, bordered by two mountain peaks.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood named George the higher of the two in honour of the king, and his companions named the other Alexander in his honour.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] They descended from the ridge towards the Shenandoah Valley: the first Westerners to set eyes and foot on it.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Crossing woods and meadows populated by elks and buffalos, after about ten kilometres they reached the bottom of the valley and the course of the Shenandoah River, which was renamed Euphrates.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Gun shots were fired here in honour of the king and a great toast was held.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood engraved the king's name on a rock and in an empty wine bottle introduced a card containing the British claim on the river and its territory.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] On September 7, the company left for Germanna, and in ten days was back in Williamsburg.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The following winter, Spotswood gave each member of the expedition a miniature gold horseshoe with engraved in Latin: *Sic juvat transcendere montes* ("This is the way to cross the mountains").
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Since then, the expedition was also known as "Knights of the Golden Horseshoe Expedition" and described by Spotswood's biographer, Walter Havighurst, as "the most romantic episode in the history of Virginia".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] It played a leading historical role not so much for the practical results it achieved, but for the impulse and the inspiration it provided for those who later wanted to venture in the exploration of the interior of the American colonies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The expedition also left considerable traces in American literature.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] A few months after the company's return, a humanities professor at the College of William & Mary, Arthur Blackamore wrote a short poem in Latin celebrating the expedition: *Expeditio Ultramontana*.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The original Latin text, considered to be among the best examples of Latin poetry in 18th century America, has been lost, but the English version that George Seagood produced in 1729 survives in its entirety.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Over a century later, in 1835, William Alexander Caruthers published a chivalric novel, *The Knights of the Golden Horse-Shoe*, telling a somewhat revisited history of the expedition.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In the 20th century, the poet Gertrude Claytor wrote a commemorative poem of the Golden Horseshoe Expedition.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Engraved on a bronze plaque, in 1934 it was posted near Swift Run Gap.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The success of the Transmontane Expedition was welcomed in the London administrative offices, but in less than a year a severe blow to the Spotswood's peace of mind came from the capital.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] At the beginning of the year 1717, a large group of influential London merchants wrote a letter to the Board of Trade declaring that the legislation promoted by Spotswood harmed the commercial interests of both the motherland and Virginia itself.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The merchants reported that, due to the corruption of the inspectors by the landowners, the lower quality production was not only still on the market – in contradiction with the purposes of the *Tobacco Inspection Act* – but had actually overtaken the higher quality varieties.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The Virginia Indian Company's monopoly on trade with Indians also deprived the merchants of a lucrative market, and this, coupled with heavy export regulations, made their activities unprofitable.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The merchants therefore asked for the abolition of those laws which they considered an obstacle to the development of trade.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The king thus put a veto on the *Tobacco Inspection Act* and on the *Indian Trade Act*, and Spotswood was forced to revoke both.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] William Byrd, in a letter from England to Philip Ludwell, a member of the Governor's Council, wrote that he had contributed to the abrogation of those laws and to the weakening of the position and influence of the governor.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The House of Burgesses opposed public funding of Fort Christanna, which had to be dismantled as a consequence, although Spotswood feared that this would destabilise the border, leaving local Indian tribes without British support and at the mercy of the Carolina tribes.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] This put an end to the *Indian Trade Act*, but not to the principles it sought to implement, which remained central in Spotswood's policy for years to come.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] As for the *Tobacco Inspection Act*, on the other hand, years later, in 1730, the same measures were successfully re-proposed and did not meet as strong an opposition as previously.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In all probability, the hostility of the House of Burgesses, rather than to a genuine intention to favour trade, was due to its tendency to oppose the actions of the governor, who had been fighting for years with the representatives for the effective control of the colony.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During this period of time, in addition to William Byrd's mission to London, other members of the Governor's Council were openly taking position against Spotswood.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The most determined among them was the Reverend James Blair, delegate of the Bishop of London and president of the College of William & Mary, one of the most powerful men in the colony, who had already been behind the dismissal of past governors Edmund Andros and Francis Nicholson.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The reason for this opposition was once again to be found in the resistance, on the part of the Virginians, to royal prerogatives affirmed by Spotswood, who claimed for the governor the right to appoint judges in criminal trials (through procedures called *oyer and terminer*).
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The members of the council, on the other hand, claimed to be the only ones entitled to do so.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In any case, the Virginian popular opinion supported the governor, who was particularly popular with the small landowners, the yeomen class.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] And, despite Byrd's scheming against him in London and the revocation of his laws, Spotswood still enjoyed the protection of the King's ministers and of the members of the Board of Trade.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In a letter sent in August 1717 to Secretary of State Joseph Addison, Spotswood reported that the only sources of concern left to impair the peace and quiet of the colony were piracy and the aggressive nature of the Indians.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Just a few months earlier, several armed Seneca gangs had moved from the Province of New York to the Virginia border, where they had engaged in raids and robberies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In March 1717, some chiefs of the Catawba tribe had gone to Fort Christanna to discuss a trade treaty with the British and Spotswood, who had long-awaited the good disposition of the Indians, had joined them.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In the days of the meeting an episode took place which risked compromising the negotiations.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] One night, some Seneca or Mohawk Indians – enemies of the Catawba – entered the fort, where the governor was lying asleep, and killed some members of the delegation, who were not bearing arms as Spotswood had imposed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Initially, the Catawba accused the British of having betrayed them and started to leave, but Spotswood, who was in danger of seeing his plans to secure the border undermined, sent a contingent to recover the abducted, reaffirmed his friendship with the Indians, and promised them greater protection.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In the end, the Catawba agreed to trade at Fort Christanna and leave some of their children there to study, and the border situation seemed to improve, at least temporarily.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The other looming threat were the pirates, who attacked ports and robbed ships, greatly hampering trade.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The most famous and feared among them, Edward Teach, who went down in history as Blackbeard, had recently returned to sail the seas, having received the King's pardon and having later surrendered to the governor of North Carolina, Charles Eden, who was probably in cahoots with him.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] When Blackbeard attacked a convoy of ships in front of Charleston Harbor in May 1718, looting and taking prisoners, the Carolina residents sought help from neighbouring Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Although he did not have a specific mandate from the king – which was necessary for the arrest and trial of pirates –, Spotswood decided to intervene, wary of Carolina's possibilities of dealing with the problem.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] He quickly had former *Queen Anne's Revenge* quartermaster William Howard arrested, who had apparently retired from piracy and lived in Virginia, suspecting that he was still in contact with Blackbeard.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] From Howard, later pardoned, he learned that Blackbeard was with a few men in one of his usual shelters, the Ocracoke Inlet.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Ocracoke was in North Carolina, out of his jurisdiction, but Spotswood was now determined to capture the pirate as quickly as possible, dead or alive, even by violating the sovereignty of another colony.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] So, without waiting for the authorization of the House of Burgesses, he sent two warships against Blackbeard under the command of Navy Lieutenant Robert Maynard.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] On November 22, 1718, after five days of search, the pirates were taken by surprise.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Maynard, aboard HMS *Pearl*, attacked Blackbeard's ship, who was killed in a short and bloody fight.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Nine of his men died with him, and Maynard lost a dozen of his men.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Two days later, Maynard returned to Jamestown with fifteen prisoners, who were later hanged, and Blackbeard's severed head was stuck on the tip of the bowsprit.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The apparent quiet at the borders was the background of new conflicts within the colony.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Some members of the House of Burgesses published a controversial pamphlet in which they reported of illegal proceedings on the part of Spotswood and in particular of the lack of prior consultation with Governor Eden.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] It appears that Spotswood was highly likely aware of Eden's political weaknesses and of his compromises with the pirates, and that he purposely omitted to seek his cooperation.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] At the same time, relations with the Governor's Council also reached a critical point.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In the early months of 1719, with the dispute over the pirates unresolved, a hard dispute arose over the powers of some sectors of the Church.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Led by James Blair and other members of the council, a first group was in favour of the current law which provided for the clergy to be directly appointed by an assembly of parishioners and without the approval of the governor.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Both sides turned to the Bishop of London, accusing each other of interference and abuse of power.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The Bishop of London then called for an assembly of all the clergymen of Virginia to take place in Williamsburg in April at the College of William & Mary, in the presence of Blair and Spotswood.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] This growing hostility of the council had already manifested itself during the previous year and Spotswood, unable to bring it under control, had tried to change its composition.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In November 1718, he asked the Board of Trade to remove some advisers hostile to him, including Blair and Byrd, who was still in London, and to replace them with men he trusted.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The Board of Trade did not fully comply with Spotswood's requests: only two of the men he proposed were appointed and the only councillor removed, Byrd – who returned to Virginia early in 1720 – was almost immediately reinstated.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Unable to get rid of them, the governor tried to make peace with the members of the council.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Byrd, who was now resident in Virginia and could therefore be more easily controlled, became Spotswood's point of reference.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The two met at the Capitol and resolved to cooperate.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] On April 29, 1720, during the next assembly of the council, the governor and the councillors officially declared their resolve to work in harmony from then on.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In this more relaxed situation, Spotswood obtained land concessions near Germanna and the western frontier, for a total of approximately 86,000 acres, where he began to build his private residence.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The Spotswood estate formed the core of the Spotsylvania County, which was established in 1720 in his honour.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Meanwhile, the buildings of the Governor's Palace and of the Bruton Parish Church in Williamsburg, which Spotswood had personally collaborated to design, were completed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The Governor's palace, in particular, was the subject of criticism for its pomp and excessive costs, but its architecture was appreciated, so much so that in its time it became a model for all residences of prestige.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The truce made official in 1720, although sincerely wanted by the parties involved, appears as a prelude to the final attack against Spotswood.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During the summer of the following year, Byrd and Blair left for England, there to reiterate more forcefully their efforts against the governor.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Despite the territorial expansion established with the Expedition over the mountains, Spotswood deemed it necessary for Great Britain to expand further northwest, as far as the Great Lakes, to gain strategic advantage in view of an imminent war against the French.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] He had already obtained an accurate map of the entire western area of the Mississippi River System, hitherto virtually unknown to the British, to be used for an expedition to Lake Erie, where Spotswood intended to establish a settlement.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In February 1720, Spotswood proposed to go on a secret mission to London to present these ideas to the government and to illustrate in detail how it was possible and necessary to conquer Spanish Florida by attacking the Spaniards in St.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Augustine, in order to prevent the French fleet from entering the waters of the Thirteen colonies from the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The secret missions never took place, and Spotswood, during his last two years as governor, concentrated instead on resolving the Indian question.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] If piracy was in rapid decline after Blackbeard's death, the problems caused by the hostile and bellicose Indian tribes were increasingly worrying.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The first outbreak was on the Maryland border, and was fuelled by hostilities between the neighbouring tribes and those of Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In the fall of 1720, tribes from Maryland attacked plantations in the Northern Neck, whereupon Spotswood, with the support of the governor of Maryland, called a meeting with the ambassadors of the five Iroquois Confederation tribes who were in conflict with the Virginia Indians.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During the meeting, which took place in Williamsburg in October 1721, three of the five ambassadors died, possibly poisoned.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Despite this event, of which the Iroquois suspected the Virginia Indians, an agreement was reached by which the Potomac River became the frontier between the Indians of Virginia and the Iroquois, and no Indian was to cross it without the authorization of the British.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Encouraged by the results, Spotswood began organizing a general meeting with the Iroquois tribes and their *Sachems* (supreme leaders), with the collaboration with the governors of Maryland, Pennsylvania, and New York.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] By June 1722, the time was ripe for Spotswood to sail from Virginia with one delegate from the Governor's Council and one from the House of Burgesses, and many gifts for the Iroquois from the Virginia Indians and from the colony's government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] He set sail for New York and from there, along with Pennsylvania governor William Keith and some New York government spokesmen, he left by land for the city of Albany, located on the banks of the Hudson River.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The delegation, which arrived in Albany on August 20, was the most representative the British had ever set up in the Thirteen Colonies, and their commitment must have impressed the Indians.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Within a few days they were joined by the leaders and warriors of the Mohicans, Oneida, Cayuga, Onondaga, and Seneca; practically all the nations in the Iroquois Confederation, followed later by the Powhatans and other tribes from Virginia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] He gave the Indian Chiefs pearl necklaces as a gift to demonstrate British good will.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Then he asked officially for confirmation of their commitment of the previous year to put an end to the raids in Piedmont and to respect the natural boundaries of the Blue Ridge Mountains and of the Potomac River.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The Indians took about ten days to answer, then the agreement, which was Spotswood's main objective, was ratified.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood also made a personal gift to the Indians of fine fabrics and work tools.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Then he left by ship along the Hudson River, heading for the open sea.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] When he arrived in Williamsburg, Spotswood learned that, despite the popular support he enjoyed, the king had decided to revoke his position as governor.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] On September 25, with Spotswood back in Williamsburg, James Blair, who had been absent for the past 12 months, and the new governor, Hugh Drysdale, an Irishman, arrived in the New World on the same ship.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The Drysdale nomination, dated April 3, 1722, was made official and Drysdale was sworn in as governor on September 27.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Historians are in disaccord when explaining the reasons behind the removal of Spotswood from office.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Walter Havighurst identified Spotswood's character as main cause; a strong, sharp, and sometimes authoritarian character, prone to the regime of obedience in the military tradition, which the Virginia aristocracy was neither used to nor willing to accept.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In fact, during the twelve years at the helm in Virginia, the governor ended up into a conflict with each one of the strong powers of the colony, as well as with the more influential of his own men, from merchants to large landowners.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The causes of his removal, which are never explicitly expressed in the official documents of the time, must be sought, according to Havighurst, in the controversy over the *oyer and terminer* courts, or over the more recent controversy on the clergymen's appointment.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The evaluations of Spotswood's contemporaries were also discordant.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Harsh criticisms of some aspects of his work can be found in the writings of James Blair and William Byrd, whose letters have been preserved.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Equally high praise, however, can be found in Robert Beverley (see his *History and Present State of Virginia*), who was one of the first historians born in Virginia, as well as Spotswood's companion in the Transmontane Expedition.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Another Spotswood's political ally, Hugh Jones, professor at the College of William & Mary, wrote in 1724, (*The Present State of Virginia*), that Virginia had become more civilised in the twelve years of Spotswood's tenure than in the previous one hundred years.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Among modern historians prevails a generally positive opinion about the Spotswood administration: brilliant and significant in its character; a strong guide in a period of economic growth and cultural development.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Historian John Fiske, in the late nineteenth century, described Spotswood as one of the best and most capable governors of the British colonial period in America and praised him in particular for the founding of the Germanna smelting plant and for the audacity of the Transmontane Expedition.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The same opinion was expressed by historian Virginius Dabney, who described Spotswood as the most celebrated among the governors of Virginia during the colonial period.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] After the experience of government, Spotswood moved to his private residence situated along the Rappahannock River, near Germanna, where he devoted himself to the administration of his large estate and to the management of his metallurgical enterprise.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Part of the production of iron and cast iron was exported to England and the rest was destined to the local market.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] For the other activities, mining and agriculture, Spotswood made use at first of the Palatine refugees he had introduced in Germanna almost ten years earlier, and when the contract that bound them to him expired, he resorted to slaves from Africa.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood's activities also included raising livestock, producing naval supplies, pitch, tar, and turpentine.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] However, having assigned land to himself in large quantities during his tenure as governor, he was accused in some circles of land grabbing.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] So, with the intention of coming to an advantageous agreement with the British Government in London on the amount of taxes due, and at the same time consolidating his right of ownership, Spotswood left for England in 1724.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] His stay in England lasted longer than expected on account of some complications, which included quantifying the extension of the land in his possession and the amount of tax to be paid.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Up till now, at age forty-eight, Spotswood had remained a bachelor waiting for the opportunity to marry a woman of high social standing.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Now, on this occasion and in the capital, shortly after his arrival, Spotswood married Anne Butler Brayne, born in 1700, the daughter of a London esquire and godchild of James Butler, 2nd Duke of Ormond.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] They had four children, two boys and two girls.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Having obtained favourable tax conditions, in February 1729 Spotswood crossed the Atlantic for the fourth and final time, with his wife and children.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During his absence, the volume of production in the metallurgical plant had dropped and some slaves had escaped, but this had not affected the activities in the estate as a whole.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] On the contrary, the prolonged active state of the furnaces made this the first stable site of this type in all of North America.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] As a private citizen, Spotswood financed the construction of a church in Germanna and began building another private residence in his own forest along the Rappahannock River.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The structure, which was destroyed in the 1750s, had a park and a cherry tree boulevard, and was larger than the Williamsburg Governor's Palace.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During this period, Spotswood made peace with William Byrd.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] After the completion of the building Byrd wrote a detailed description of the residence, which he called an "enchanted castle", and of the solitary and measured lifestyle of its owner.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During this time, Spotswood acquired another property near Yorktown, called Temple Farm.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] A few decades later the house, known as Moore House from the surname of Spotswood's son-in-law who inherited it, was the theatre of a crucial episode of the American Revolution, when in 1781 General Charles Cornwallis signed the final British surrender.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] During the last few years of his life, Spotswood stayed away from the frenzy of political life.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] At the time of Byrd's visit, some ministers in London were thinking of offering him (as Byrd testifies) the post of governor of the colony of Jamaica, with the task of taking Spanish Havana with a military action.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] However, nothing came of it, as it was eventually decided to resort to more peaceful ways of dealing with the Spaniards.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood accepted instead a less up-front mandate, which allowed him to return to projects developed during his years as governor: in 1730 he was appointed with a ten-year term Deputy Postmaster General of British America.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] At the time, the postal system covered only the coastal strip extending from New England to Pennsylvania up to Philadelphia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Virginia, cut off from courier routes, received mail once every two weeks.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In 1732, Spotswood extended the postal system to Williamsburg, where the mail started to arrive on a weekly basis.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood also entered into a partnership with the young publisher Benjamin Franklin, with whom he developed a personal friendship, appointing him, in 1737, postmaster for his city, Philadelphia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In October 1739, due to the constant attacks on the English merchant navy by Spanish naval ships, Britain declared war on Spain.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The conflict would go down in history as the war of Jenkins' Ear, named after an English captain whose ear was cut off by the Spaniards.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood, who had not lost interest in military affairs, proposed to the general command of London that he personally recruit a regiment of volunteers to be employed in South America.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Having obtained approval, he was appointed major general and quartermaster of the troops stationed in America, crowning thus with a promotion his military career.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] He was to be the leader and the organiser of a military expedition against the Spanish stronghold of Cartagena de Indias, in present-day Colombia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] At the beginning of the following May, Spotswood travelled to Annapolis, Maryland, to consult with the local governors, wait there for the arrival of his troops and later to set sail with them.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] But in Annapolis he was taken ill, and his death came quickly, on June 7, 1740, at the age of sixty-four.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] The expedition to Cartagena was postponed for a year, when the British forces placed the city under siege, but were utterly defeated.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] Spotswood's body was probably buried in Annapolis, but it is possible that it was brought back home to his Temple Farm property near Yorktown and buried near the York River.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] In any case, the memory of Spotswood, and in particular of his government, lasted in Williamsburg for a long time to come.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alexander-spotswood] It was revealed in episode 4 of the 10th season of *Who Do You Think You Are?* that through his daughter, Dorothea, Alexander Spotswood was pop star Hilary Duff's seventh great-grandfather.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The quotation "**all men are created equal**" is found in the United States Declaration of Independence and is a phrase that has come to be seen as emblematic of America's founding ideals.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The final form of the sentence was stylized by Benjamin Franklin, and penned by Thomas Jefferson during the beginning of the Revolutionary War in 1776.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Drawing from Enlightenment philosophy, the phrase reflects the influence of John Locke's second treatise on government, particularly his belief in the inherent equality and individual liberty.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Similar ideas can be traced back to earlier works, including medieval and classical sources, which emphasized the dignity and worth of all human beings.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Jefferson applied the concept in his original draft of the declaration.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The phrase was subsequently quoted and incorporated into the speeches and writings of prominent figures throughout American political and social history.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The phrase is attested as early as pope Gregory the Great in book XXI of his *Moralia in Job* (c.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] 595). and was picked up by Thomas Aquinas, Azo, Hervaeus Natalis, and other medieval thinkers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Thomas Jefferson, a key figure in drafting the Declaration of Independence, was heavily influenced by French Enlightenment philosophers such as Voltaire, Rousseau and Montesquieu, largely through his friendship with the Marquis de Lafayette.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] These philosophers, whose writings were often censored, advocated that men were born free and equal.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Their ideas profoundly impacted the French Revolution of 1789 and the development of the concept of human rights (*droits de l'homme*).
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] At the age of 33, Jefferson may also have drawn inspiration from his Italian friend and neighbor Filippo Mazzei, as claimed by John F.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Kennedy in *A Nation of Immigrants* and by Joint Resolution 175 of the 103rd Congress.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Additionally, Jefferson might have been influenced by Thomas Paine's *Common Sense*, which was published in early 1776.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] In English history there exist earlier uses of nearly the same phrase.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] First by the medieval priest John Ball who at the outbreak of the 1381 Peasants Revolt in his famous sermon posited the question "When Adam delved and Eve span, Who was then the gentleman?" and proclaimed "From the beginning all men by nature were created alike".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] In his 1690 work Second Treatise of Government the philosopher John Locke argues that in the "state of nature" that existed before the formation of governments all men were created equal.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Another example is in John Milton's 1649 book called The Tenure of Kings and Magistrates, written after the First English Civil War to defend the actions and rights of the Parliamentary cause, in the wake of the execution of king Charles I.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The English poet says: "No man who knows ought, can be so stupid to deny that all men naturally were borne free, being the image and resemblance of God himself ... born to command and not to obey: and that they liv'd so".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] In 1776, the Second Continental Congress asked Benjamin Franklin, Thomas Jefferson, John Adams, Robert Livingston, and Roger Sherman to write the Declaration of Independence.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] This Committee of Five voted to have Thomas Jefferson write the document.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] After Jefferson finished he gave the document to Franklin to proof.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Thomas Jefferson, a competent Virginia lawyer, saw this as a problem in legal writing and chose words that were more acceptable to the Second Continental Congress.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The plaintiffs in the cases of *Brom and Bett v.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Nathaniel Jennison* argued that this provision abolished slavery in Massachusetts.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The latter case resulted in a "sweeping declaration . . . that the institution of slavery was incompatible with the principles of liberty and legal equality articulated in the new Massachusetts Constitution".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The phrase has since been considered a hallmark statement in democratic constitutions and similar human rights instruments, many of which have adopted the phrase or variants thereof.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] In the early 19th century, the phrase attracted criticism from proslavery politicians.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Virginia Senator John Randolph of Roanoke criticized the phrase, stating that it was "a falsehood, and a most pernicious falsehood, even though I find it in the Declaration of Independence".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Calhoun concurred with this view, saying that there was "not a word of truth" in the phrase.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] In 1853, speaking in regard to the Kansas–Nebraska Act, Indiana Senator John Pettit said that the phrase was not a "self-evident truth" but a "self-evident lie".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Howard Zinn and others have written that the phrase is sexist.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Zinn says that the use of the word *men*, to the exclusion of women, indicated the women were "beyond consideration as worthy of inclusion" and "they were simply overlooked in any consideration of political rights, any notions of civic equality".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] However, others argue that in the 1700s, the word *men* was sometimes used to denote both genders*.* According to the Library of Congress, most people have interpreted "all men*"* to mean humanity and, within the context of the times, it is clear that "all men" meant "humanity".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] It has also been criticized on grounds of racism.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The truth is we're a bigoted people and always have been".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Weaver, in one of the cornerstone works of traditional conservatism, *Ideas Have Consequences* (1948), paraphrased a 19th-century writer, stating that "no man was ever created free and no two men [were] ever created equal".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] He continued: "The comity of peoples in groups large or small rests not upon this chimerical notion of equality but upon fraternity, a concept which long antedates it in history because it goes immeasurably deeper in human sentiment.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The ancient feeling of brotherhood carries obligations of which equality knows nothing.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The contradiction between the claim that "all men are created equal" and the existence of American slavery, including Jefferson himself owning hundreds of slaves, attracted comment when the Declaration of Independence was first published.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Before final approval, Congress, having made a few alterations to some of the wording, also deleted nearly a fourth of the draft, including a passage criticizing the slave trade.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] At that time many other members of Congress also owned slaves, which clearly factored into their decision to delete the controversial "anti-slavery" passage.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Senator Benjamin Wade defended the phrase in 1854, stating that all men are created equal in the sense that they are "equal in point of right" so "no man has a right to trample upon another".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] According to Abraham Lincoln, the founders did not mean that "all were equal in color, size, intellect, moral developments, or social capacity" but rather that everyone was equal in having "certain inalienable rights, among which are life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Also in defense of the phrase, Stanford University historian Jack Rakove said that the founders were not referring to the equality of individuals but to the right to self-government enjoyed by all peoples.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] It was only later, in the decades following the Revolution, said Rakove, that the statement came to be interpreted in reference to personal liberties.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The Proclamation of Independence of the Democratic Republic of Vietnam, written in 1945, uses the phrase "all men are created equal" and also mentions the United States Declaration of Independence in it.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The Rhodesia's Unilateral Declaration of Independence, ratified in November 1965, is based on the American one, however, it omits the phrase "all men are created equal", along with "the consent of the governed".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The sentiment of the phrase, although not the exact wording, is echoed in numerous subsequent declarations of rights, including the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms, Germany's Basic Laws, the Constitution of Algeria, and many other constitutions.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] The phrase often serves as the first, or one of the first, rights listed in enumerations of rights, as a framing for all subsequent rights.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/all-men-are-created-equal] Since Declarations of rights are often applied to all people, as natural human rights, the phrase emphasizes that all rights listed after it apply equally to every person.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] In its earliest usage, *alma mater* was an honorific title for various mother goddesses, especially Ceres or Cybele.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] Later, in Catholicism, it became a title for Mary, mother of Jesus.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] By the early 17th century, the nursing mother became an allegory for universities.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] Used by many schools in Europe and North America, it has special association with the University of Bologna, whose motto *Alma Mater Studiorum* ("nurturing mother of studies") emphasizes its role in originating the modern university.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] Several university campuses in North America display artistic representations of *Alma Mater*, depicted as a robed woman wearing a laurel wreath crown.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] The earliest and of these is the bronze *Alma Mater* statue at Columbia University, designed in 1901 by Daniel Chester French.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] In the US the term *alma mater* is often used to describe a school song.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] Although *alma* (nourishing) was a common epithet for Ceres, Cybele, Venus, and other mother goddesses, it was not frequently used in conjunction with *mater* in classical Latin.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] After the fall of Rome, the term was used in Christian liturgy to describe Jesus' mother, Mary.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] "Alma Redemptoris Mater" is a well-known eleventh century antiphon devoted to Mary.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] The earliest documented use of the term to refer to a university is in 1600, when the University of Cambridge printer, John Legate, began using an emblem for the university press.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] The first-known appearance of the device is in William Perkins', *A Golden Chain*, a book first printed by Legate in 1600.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] On the title-page, the Latin phrase *Alma Mater Cantabrigia* ("nourishing mother Cambridge") is inscribed on a pedestal bearing a lactating woman wearing a mural crown.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] In reference works of English etymology, often the first university-related usage is cited as 1710, when an academic mother figure is mentioned in a remembrance of Henry More by Richard Ward.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] Many historic European universities have adopted *Alma Mater* as part of the Latin translation of their official name.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] The Latin name of the University of Bologna, *Alma Mater Studiorum* (nourishing mother of studies), refers to its status as the oldest continuously operating university in the world.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] At other European universities, such as the Alma Mater Lipsiensis in Leipzig, Germany, or Alma Mater Jagiellonica, Poland, the title emphasizes historic ties to a founding city or dynasty.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] The Alma Mater Europaea in Salzburg, Austria, an international university founded by the European Academy of Sciences and Arts in 2010, uses the term as its official name.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] In the United States, the College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia, has been called the "Alma Mater of the Nation" because of its ties to the founding of the country.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] At Queen's University in Kingston, Ontario, and the University of British Columbia in Vancouver, British Columbia, the main student government is known as the Alma Mater Society.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] Sculptures of *Alma Mater* are found on several North American university campuses.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] In 1901, to commemorate the opening of the Low Library, Columbia University commissioned Daniel Chester French to design a bronze statue for the library's steps.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] French chose the *Alma Mater* to allegorically embody the university without depicting its founder, King George II.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] A similar sculpture, cast in 1919 by Mario Korbel, sits on the main entrance steps at the University of Havana.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] Other tributes to *Alma Mater* include Lorado Taft's *1929 sculpture* at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign and Cyrus Dallin's 1925 sculpture at the Mary Institute in 1925, commissioned by Washington University supporters.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/alma-mater] An altarpiece mural in Yale University's Sterling Memorial Library, painted in 1932 by Eugene Savage, depicts the *Alma Mater* as a bearer of light and truth, standing in the midst of figures representing the arts and sciences.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The **American Revolution** (1765–1789) was a political movement in the Thirteen Colonies of Great Britain.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The movement began as a rebellion and evolved into a revolution resulting in the sovereign United States.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] These changes were the outcome of the associated American Revolutionary War.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress, as the provisional government, established the Continental Army and appointed George Washington as its commander-in-chief in 1775.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The following year, the Congress passed the Lee Resolution on July 2nd, then unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence on the Fourth of July.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Throughout most of the war, the outcome appeared uncertain.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] However, in 1781, a decisive victory by Washington and the Continental Army in the Siege of Yorktown led King George III and the Fox–North coalition in government to negotiate the cessation of colonial rule and the acknowledgment of American sovereignty, formalized in the Treaty of Paris in 1783.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Constitution took effect in 1789 and the Bill of Rights was ratified in 1791.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Discontent with colonial rule began shortly after the French and Indian War ended in 1763.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Even though the colonies had fought in and supported the war directly with troops, funds and material, the British Parliament imposed new taxes to ostensibly compensate for wartime costs, and transferred control of the colonies' western lands to British officials in Montreal.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Representatives from several colonies convened in New York City for the Stamp Act Congress in 1765; its "Declaration of Rights and Grievances" argued that this taxation without representation in Parliament and other policies violated their rights as Englishmen.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In 1767, though the Stamp Act was repealed, tensions flared again following Parliament's passage of the Townshend Acts.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In an effort to quell the mounting rebellion, King George III deployed British troops to the colony of Massachusetts, where they killed antagonists in the 1770 Boston Massacre.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In December 1773, the local faction of the colonies-wide Sons of Liberty underground orchestrated the Boston Tea Party, during which they dumped chests of taxed tea owned by the British East India Company into Boston Harbor.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Parliament responded by enacting a series of punitive laws, intended to end self-government in Massachusetts, but instead increased American support for the revolutionary cause.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In 1774, twelve of the Thirteen Colonies sent delegates to the First Continental Congress; the Province of Georgia joined in 1775.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The First Continental Congress began coordinating Patriot resistance through underground networks of committees largely built on the foundations of the Sons of Liberty network.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In August 1775, King George III proclaimed Massachusetts to be in a state of rebellion.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British attempted to disarm the colonists, resulting in the Battles of Lexington and Concord, sparking the Revolutionary War.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress convened in May of 1775 and created the Continental Army, which then surrounded Boston, forcing the British to withdraw by sea in March 1776 and leaving Patriots in control in every colony.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In May 1776, Congress voted to suppress all forms of Crown authority, to be replaced by locally created authority, and each colony created a state constitution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On July 2, the Congress passed the Lee Resolution, affirming their support for joint independence.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On July 4, 1776 they unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence, famously proclaiming that "all men are created equal", having then evolved from a rebellion over British rights to a revolution based on universal rights.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Congress soon after began deliberating the Articles of Confederation, an effort to establish a multi-state self-governing coordinating body capable of negotiating international treaties and prosecuting the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Revolutionary War continued for another five years during which France ultimately entered, supporting the revolutionary cause.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On September 28, 1781, Washington commanded the Continental Army's capture of a British army under General Cornwallis at the Siege of Yorktown, leading to the collapse of King George's control of Parliament.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Consensus in Parliament soon shifted to the war ending on American terms.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On September 3, 1783, the British signed the Treaty of Paris, recognizing the sovereign independence of the United States, and ceding to the new nation nearly all the territory east of the Mississippi River and south of the Great Lakes.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The United States became the first nation to establish a federal republic with a written constitution based on the principles of universal natural rights, consent of the governed, and equality under the law, albeit with significant democratic limitations compared to later evolution of the concept.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] After the Glorious Revolution in Great Britain, it unofficially adopted a policy of "salutary neglect," whereby the Thirteen Colonies were largely left to govern themselves.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] This British policy reverted significantly after the French and Indian War.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British political establishment, especially after taking massive swaths of land from the former territories of New France, pursued a policy of greater control over colonial affairs, prompting the Thirteen Colonies to seek restoration of greater autonomy from Britain.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] After the American Revolution one Patriot, Capt.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Levi Preston of Danvers, Massachusetts, who was asked why the Americans rebelled against England, responded: "...we always had governed ourselves, and we always meant to.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Thirteen Colonies were established in the 17th century as part of the English Empire and became parts of the British Empire after the union of England and Scotland in 1707.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The development of a unique American identity can be traced to the English Civil War (1642–1651) and its aftermath.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In that period the Puritan colonies of New England supported the Commonwealth government responsible for the execution of King Charles I.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] After the Stuart Restoration of 1660, Massachusetts did not recognize Charles II as the legitimate king for more than a year after his coronation.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In King Philip's War (1675–1678), the New England colonies fought a coalition of a few Native American tribes without military assistance from England, thereby contributing to the development of a uniquely American identity separate from that of the British people.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In the 1680s, Charles and his brother, James II, attempted to bring New England under direct English control.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The colonists fiercely opposed this, and the Crown nullified their colonial charters in response.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In 1686, James finalized these efforts by consolidating the separate New England colonies along with New York and New Jersey into the Dominion of New England.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Edmund Andros was appointed royal governor and tasked with governing the new Dominion under his direct rule.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Colonial assemblies and town meetings were restricted, new local taxes were levied, and rights were abridged.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Dominion rule triggered bitter resentment throughout New England.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] When James tried to rule without Parliament, the English aristocracy removed him from power in the Glorious Revolution of 1688.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] This was followed by the 1689 Boston revolt, which overthrew Dominion rule.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Colonial governments reasserted their control after the revolt.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The new monarchs, William and Mary, granted new charters to the individual New England colonies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] After the Glorious Revolution, the British Empire became a constitutional monarchy with sovereignty in the King-in-Parliament.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Aristocrats inherited seats in the House of Lords, while the gentry and merchants controlled the elected House of Commons.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The king ruled through cabinet ministers who depended on majority support in the Commons to govern effectively.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] British subjects on both sides of the Atlantic proudly claimed that the unwritten British constitution, with its guarantees of the rights of Englishmen, protected personal liberty better than any other government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British constitution served as the model for colonial governments.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Crown appointed a royal governor in each colony to exercise executive power, usually also appointing a Governor's Council largely to act as an unelected upper chamber of the legislature.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Property owners elected a colonial assembly amongst themselves with powers to legislate and levy taxes, but the British government reserved the right to veto colonial legislation.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British government lacked the resources and information necessary for close supervision of the colonies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Instead, British officials negotiated and compromised with colonial leaders to gain compliance with imperial policies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The colonies defended themselves with provincial troops and colonial militias of locals, and the British government rarely sent military forces to America before 1755.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] According to historian Robert Middlekauff, "Americans had become almost completely self-governing" before the American Revolution, a practice that was consistent with the British monarchy's practice of salutary neglect.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] With little industry except shipbuilding, the colonies exported agricultural products in return for manufactured goods.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] They also imported molasses, rum, and sugar from the British West Indies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In 1651, Parliament passed the first in a series of Navigation Acts, which restricted colonial trade with foreign countries.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British government pursued this policy of mercantilism in order to grow its economic and political power.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] According to mercantilism, the colonies existed for the mother country's economic benefit, and the colonists' economic needs were largely inconsequential.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Thirteen Colonies could trade with the rest of the empire but only ship certain commodities like tobacco to Britain.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Any European imports bound for British America had to first pass through an English port and pay customs duties.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Other laws regulated the developing colonial industries to prevent competition with industries in Britain, such as the Wool Act 1698, the Hat Act 1731, and the Iron Act 1750.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Colonial reactions to these policies were mixed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Molasses Act 1733, for example, placed a duty of six pence per gallon upon foreign molasses imported into the colonies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] This act was particularly egregious to the New England colonists, who protested it as unconstitutional taxation without representation in the British parliament.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The act increased the smuggling of foreign molasses, and the British government ceased enforcement efforts after the 1740s.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On the other hand, certain merchants and local industries benefited from the restrictions on foreign competition.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The limits on foreign-built ships greatly benefited the colonial shipbuilding industry, particularly in New England.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Some argue that the economic impact was minimal on the colonists, but the political friction that the acts triggered was more serious, as the merchants most directly affected were also the most politically active.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] During the French and Indian War (1754–1763), the British government fielded 45,000 soldiers, half British Regulars and half colonial volunteers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The colonies also contributed funds and materiel to the war effort; though, two-fifths of this spending was reimbursed by the British government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Great Britain defeated France and acquired that nation's territory east of the Mississippi River.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In order to allow approximately 1,500 politically well-connected British Army officers to remain on active duty in America with full pay after the war, the Bute ministry decided in early 1763 to permanently garrison 10,000 soldiers in North America.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Due to long-established English resistance to a standing army, stationing these officers in Great Britain during peacetime was a politically unacceptable alternative.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The excuse made for a standing army in America was defense against French troops stationed in the West Indies, and foreign populations in newly acquired territories (the French in Canada and the Spanish in Florida).
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In addition, British soldiers were supposed to help collect customs duties and prevent colonists from instigating conflict with Native Americans.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Instead, increased British migration beyond the Appalachian Mountains and Native American anger over the policies of General Jeffery Amherst caused Pontiac's War (1763–1766).
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In response, the Grenville ministry issued the Royal Proclamation of 1763, designating the territory between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River an Indian Reserve closed to colonial settlement.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Proclamation angered settlers, fur traders, and land speculators; however, it failed to stop westward migration.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Stationing troops in North America on a permanent basis would cost another £360,000 a year.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On a per capita basis, Grenville claimed Americans paid 1 shilling in taxes directly to the empire (not including local taxes) compared to 26 shillings paid by the English.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The enslaved, a near majority of the population in some colonies, did not pay any taxes and therefore skewed this comparison.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On March 9, 1764, Grenville proposed the Sugar Act, which was enacted by Parliament in April.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] It lowered the duty on foreign molasses from 6 pence to 3 pence per gallon.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Treasury believed it would generate £78,000.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] To ensure this money could be collected, the act strengthened efforts against smuggling.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Customs officials could choose whether to prosecute violators in colonial courts or vice admiralty courts.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Unlike colonial courts where there was a presumption of innocence and cases were decided by local juries who frequently acquitted accused smugglers, vice admiralty courts operated on a presumption of guilt and cases were decided by Crown-appointed judges.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On the same day he introduced the Sugar Act in Parliament, Grenville stated it might be necessary to levy stamp duties on the colonies to raise additional revenue, but he delayed action to give the colonies time to propose another way to raise the revenue.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Parliament passed the Stamp Act in March 1765, which imposed direct taxes on the colonies for the first time.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] All official documents, newspapers, almanacs, and pamphlets were required to have the stamps—even decks of playing cards.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The colonists did not object that the taxes were high; they were actually low.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] They objected to their lack of representation in the Parliament, which gave them no voice concerning legislation that affected them, such as the tax, thereby violating the unwritten English constitution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] This grievance was overly simplified with the slogan "No taxation without representation".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Shortly following adoption of the Stamp Act, factions of the Sons of Liberty formed in each colony, and began using public demonstrations, boycotts, and threats of violence to ensure that the offending British policies became unenforceable.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In Boston, the Sons of Liberty burned the records of the vice admiralty court and looted the home of chief justice Thomas Hutchinson.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Several legislatures called for united action, and nine colonies sent delegates to the Stamp Act Congress in New York City in October.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Moderates led by John Dickinson drew up a Declaration of Rights and Grievances stating in part that the colonists were equal to all other British subjects and that, among other abuses, taxes passed without representation in Parliament violated their rights as Englishmen.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Parliament at Westminster saw itself as the supreme lawmaking authority throughout the Empire and thus entitled to enact any legislation, including levying any tax, without colonial approval or even consultation.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] They argued that the colonies were legally British corporations subordinate to the British Parliament.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Parliament insisted that the colonists effectively enjoyed a "virtual representation", as most British people did, since only a small minority of the British population were eligible to elect representatives to Parliament.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] However, Americans such as James Otis maintained that there was no one in Parliament responsible specifically to any colonial constituency, so they were not "virtually represented" by anyone in Parliament.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Rockingham government came to power in July 1765, and Parliament debated whether to repeal the stamp tax or to send an army to enforce it.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Benjamin Franklin appeared before them to make the case for repeal, explaining that the colonies had spent heavily in manpower, money, and blood defending the empire, and that further taxes to pay for those wars were unjust and might bring about a rebellion.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Parliament agreed and repealed the tax on February 21, 1766, but they insisted in the Declaratory Act of March 1766 that they retained full power to make laws for the colonies "in all cases whatsoever".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The repeal nonetheless caused widespread celebrations in the colonies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In 1767, the British Parliament passed the Townshend Acts, which placed duties on several staple goods, including paper, glass, and tea, and established a Board of Customs in Boston to more rigorously execute trade regulations.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The new taxes were enacted on the belief that Americans only objected to internal taxes and not to external taxes such as custom duties.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] John Dickinson however, in his widely read pamphlet *Letters from a Farmer in Pennsylvania*, argued against the constitutionality of the acts because their purpose was to raise revenue and not to regulate trade.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Colonists responded to the taxes by organizing new boycotts of British goods.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] These boycotts were less effective, however, as the goods taxed by the Townshend Acts were widely used.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In February 1768, the Assembly of Massachusetts Bay Colony issued a circular letter to the other colonies urging them to coordinate resistance.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The governor dissolved the assembly when it refused to rescind the letter.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In June 1768 a riot broke out in Boston over the seizure of the sloop *Liberty*, owned by John Hancock, for alleged smuggling.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Customs officials were forced to flee, prompting the British to deploy troops to Boston.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] A Boston town meeting declared that no obedience was due to parliamentary laws and called for the convening of a convention.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] A convention assembled but only issued a mild protest before dissolving itself.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In January 1769, Parliament responded to the unrest by reactivating the Treason Act 1543 which called for subjects outside the realm to face trials for treason in England.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The governor of Massachusetts was instructed to collect evidence of said treason, and the threat caused widespread outrage, though it was not carried out.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On March 5, 1770, a large crowd gathered around a group of British soldiers on a Boston street.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The crowd grew threatening, throwing snowballs, rocks, and debris at them.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] There was no order to fire, but the soldiers panicked and fired into the crowd.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] They hit 11 people; three civilians died of wounds at the scene of the shooting, and two died shortly after.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The event quickly came to be called the Boston Massacre.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The soldiers were tried and acquitted (defended by American patriot John Adams), but the widespread descriptions soon began to turn colonial sentiment against the British.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] This accelerated the downward spiral in the relationship between Britain and the province of Massachusetts, and other colonies were becoming increasingly empathetic.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] A new ministry under Lord North came to power in 1770, and Parliament repealed most of the Townshend duties, except the tax on tea.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] This temporarily resolved the crisis, and the boycott of British goods largely ceased, with only the more radical patriots such as Samuel Adams continuing to agitate.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In June 1772, American patriots, including John Brown, burned a British warship that had been vigorously enforcing unpopular trade regulations, in what became known as the *Gaspee* Affair.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The affair was investigated for possible treason, but no action was taken.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In 1773, private letters were published in which Massachusetts Governor Thomas Hutchinson claimed that the colonists could not enjoy all English liberties, and in which Lieutenant Governor Andrew Oliver called for the direct payment of colonial officials, which had been paid by local authorities.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] This would have reduced the influence of colonial representatives over their government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The letters' contents were used as evidence of a systematic plot against American rights, and discredited Hutchinson in the eyes of the people; the colonial Assembly petitioned for his recall.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Benjamin Franklin, postmaster general for the colonies, acknowledged that he leaked the letters, which led to him being removed from his position.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] From Boston Samuel Adams set about creating new Committees of Correspondence, built largely on the foundations of the underground Sons of Liberty network, linking Patriots in all 13 colonies and eventually providing the framework for a provisional government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Virginia, the largest colony, set up its Committee of Correspondence in early 1773, on which Patrick Henry and Thomas Jefferson served.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] A total of about 7,000 to 8,000 Patriots served on these Committees; Loyalists were excluded.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The committees became the leaders of the American resistance to British actions, and later largely determined the war effort at the state and local level.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] When the First Continental Congress resolved to boycott British products, the colonial and local Committees took charge, examining merchant records and publishing the names of merchants who attempted to defy the boycott by importing British goods.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, Parliament passed the Tea Act lowering the price of taxed tea exported to the colonies, to help the British East India Company undersell smuggled untaxed Dutch tea.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Special consignees were appointed to sell the tea to bypass colonial merchants.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The act was opposed by those who resisted the taxes and also by smugglers who stood to lose business.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In every colony demonstrators warned merchants not to bring in tea that included the hated new tax.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In most instances, the consignees were forced by the Americans to resign and the tea was turned back, but Massachusetts governor Hutchinson refused to allow Boston merchants to give in to pressure.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] A town meeting in Boston determined that the tea would not be landed, and ignored a demand from the governor to disperse.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On December 16, 1773, a group of men, led by Samuel Adams and dressed to evoke the appearance of Indigenous people, boarded the ships of the East India Company and dumped £10,000 worth of tea from their holds (approximately £636,000 in 2008) into Boston Harbor.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Decades later, this event became known as the Boston Tea Party and remains a significant part of American patriotic lore.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British government responded by passing four laws that came to be known as the Intolerable Acts, further darkening colonial opinion towards England.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The first was the Massachusetts Government Act which altered the Massachusetts charter and restricted town meetings.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The second was the Administration of Justice Act which ordered that all British soldiers to be tried were to be arraigned in Britain, not in the colonies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The third was the Boston Port Act, which closed the port of Boston until the British had been compensated for the tea lost in the Boston Tea Party.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The fourth was the Quartering Act of 1774, which allowed royal governors to house British troops in the homes of citizens without permission of the owner.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In response, "Starting in August 1774, each time a court was slated to meet in some Massachusetts town, great numbers of angry citizens made sure it did not".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The next month Patriots issued the Suffolk Resolves and formed an alternative shadow government known as the Massachusetts Provincial Congress, which began training militia outside British-occupied Boston.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In September 1774, the First Continental Congress convened in Pennsylvania, consisting of representatives from each colony, to serve as a vehicle for deliberation and collective action.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] During secret debates, conservative Joseph Galloway proposed the creation of a colonial Parliament that would be able to approve or disapprove acts of the British Parliament, but his idea was tabled in a vote of 6 to 5 and was subsequently removed from the record.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Congress called for a boycott beginning on December 1, 1774, of all British goods; it was enforced by new local committees authorized by the Congress that were largely built upon the earlier Committees of Correspondence.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] It also began coordinating Patriot resistance by militias in each colony, including many veterans who had gained military experience in the French and Indian War.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] For the first time, the Patriots were armed and unified against Parliament.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] King George III declared Massachusetts to be in a state of rebellion in February 1775 and the British garrison received orders to seize the rebels' weapons and arrest their leaders, resulting in the Battles of Lexington and Concord on April 19, 1775.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Patriots assembled a militia 15,000 strong and laid siege to Boston, occupied by 6500 British soldiers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress convened in Philadelphia on June 14, 1775.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The congress was divided on the best course of action.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] They authorized formation of the Continental Army, appointing George Washington as its commander-in-chief, while producing the Olive Branch Petition in which they attempted to come to an accord with King George.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The king, however, would issue a Proclamation of Rebellion in August which declared that all the states were "in rebellion" and the members of Congress were traitors.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, the Battle of Bunker Hill on June 17, 1775 was a British victory—but at a great cost: about 1,000 British casualties from a garrison of about 6,000, as compared to 500 American casualties from a much larger force.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In the winter of 1775, the Americans invaded northeastern Quebec under generals Benedict Arnold and Richard Montgomery, expecting to rally sympathetic colonists there.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The attack was a failure; many Americans were killed, captured, or died of smallpox.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Following the Battle of Bunker Hill in June 1775, the Patriots had control of Massachusetts outside Boston's city limits, and the Loyalists suddenly found themselves on the defensive with no protection from the British army.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In each of the Thirteen Colonies, American patriots overthrew their existing governments, closed courts, and drove out British colonial officials.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] They held elected conventions and established their own legislatures, which existed outside any legal parameters established by the British.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] New constitutions were drawn up in each state to supersede royal charters.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] They proclaimed that they were now *states*, no longer *colonies*.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On January 5, 1776, New Hampshire ratified the first state constitution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In May 1776, Congress voted to suppress all forms of Crown authority, to be replaced by locally created authority.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] New Jersey, South Carolina, and Virginia created their constitutions before July 4.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Rhode Island and Connecticut simply took their existing royal charters and deleted all references to the Crown.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The new states were all committed to republicanism, with no inherited offices.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The radical provisions of Pennsylvania's constitution lasted 14 years.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In 1790, conservatives gained power in the state legislature, called a new constitutional convention, and rewrote the constitution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The new constitution substantially reduced universal male suffrage, gave the governor veto power and patronage appointment authority, and added an upper house with substantial wealth qualifications to the unicameral legislature.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Thomas Paine called it a constitution unworthy of America.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In March 1776, aided by the fortification of Dorchester Heights with cannons recently captured at Fort Ticonderoga, the Continental Army led by George Washington forced the British to evacuate Boston.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The revolutionaries now fully controlled all thirteen states and ready to declare joint independence.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] There still were many Loyalists, but they were no longer in control anywhere by July 1776, and all of the royal officials had fled.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In April 1776, the North Carolina Provincial Congress issued the Halifax Resolves explicitly authorizing its delegates to vote for independence.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] By June, nine state legislatures supported independence from Britain, and Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland, and New York followed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Richard Henry Lee was instructed by the Virginia legislature to propose independence, and he did so on June 7, 1776.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Gathered at Pennsylvania State House in Philadelphia, later renamed Independence Hall, 56 of the nation's Founding Fathers representing the United Colonies adopted and issued to King George III the Declaration of Independence.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] It had been drafted largely by Thomas Jefferson, and was edited and presented by the Committee of Five which was charged with authoring it.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Congress struck several provisions of the Committee's draft, and then adopted it unanimously on July 4.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Declaration embodied universal rights expressed through the political philosophies of liberalism and republicanism, rejected monarchy and aristocracy, and famously proclaimed that "all men are created equal".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] What had begun as a rebellion demanding the rights of Englishmen had now evolved into a revolution to overthrow and replace the political and social order in America based on universal rights.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] With the new state constitutions and the issuance of the Declaration of Independence, each former colony began operating as an independent and sovereign state.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The next step was to form a union to facilitate international relations and alliances.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On November 5, 1777, the Congress approved the Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union and sent it to each state for ratification.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Congress immediately began operating under the Articles' terms, providing a structure of shared sovereignty during prosecution of the Revolutionary War.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Articles were fully ratified on March 1, 1781.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] At that point, the Continental Congress was dissolved and a new government of the United States in Congress Assembled took its place the following day, with Samuel Huntington leading the Congress as presiding officer.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] It remained a unicameral body, where each state retained one vote.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] According to British historian Jeremy Black, the British had significant advantages, including a highly trained army, the world's largest navy, and an efficient system of public finance that could easily fund the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] However, they seriously misunderstood the depth of support for the American Patriot position, misinterpreting the situation as merely a large-scale riot.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In the Siege of Boston, Washington forced the British out of the city in the spring of 1776, and neither the British nor the Loyalists controlled any significant areas.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British, however, were amassing forces at their naval base at Halifax, Nova Scotia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] They returned in force in July 1776, landing in New York and defeating Washington's Continental Army toe-to-toe in August at the Battle of Brooklyn, the largest battle of the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Following that victory, and poised to take New York City, they requested a meeting with representatives from Congress to negotiate an end to hostilities.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] A delegation including John Adams and Benjamin Franklin met British admiral Richard Howe on Staten Island in New York Harbor on September 11 in what became known as the Staten Island Peace Conference.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Howe demanded that the Americans retract the Declaration of Independence, which they refused to do, and negotiations ended.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British then seized New York City and nearly captured Washington's army.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] They made the city their main political and military base of operations, holding the strategic harbor and port until November 1783.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The city became the destination for Loyalist refugees and a focal point of Washington's intelligence network.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British also took New Jersey, pushing the Continental Army into Pennsylvania.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Washington crossed the Delaware River back into New Jersey in a surprise attack in late December 1776 and defeated the Hessian and British garrisons at Trenton and Princeton, thereby regaining control of most of New Jersey.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The victories gave an important boost to Patriots at a time when morale was flagging and enlistments were ending, and they have become iconic events of the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In 1777, the British sent Burgoyne's invasion force from Canada south through New York with the aim of isolating New England to the east, which the British perceived as the primary source of agitation.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In anticipation of a coordinated British attack on the *de facto* revolutionary capital of Philadelphia, the Continental Congress was forced to temporarily depart Philadelphia in September for Baltimore, where they continued deliberations.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Rather than move north to support Burgoyne, the British army in New York City in fact went to Philadelphia in a major case of mis-coordination, capturing it from Washington.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The invasion army from Canada was much too slow and became trapped in northern New York state.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] It surrendered to the Americans after the Battles of Saratoga in October 1777.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] From early October 1777 until November 15, a siege distracted British troops at Fort Mifflin, Pennsylvania and allowed Washington time to preserve the Continental Army by safely leading his troops to harsh winter quarters at Valley Forge, some 35 miles from Philadelphia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On August 23, 1775, George III declared Americans to be traitors to the Crown if they took up arms against royal authority.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] There were thousands of British and Hessian soldiers in American hands following their surrender at the Battles of Saratoga.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Lord Germain took a hard line, but the British generals on American soil never held treason trials, and instead treated captured American soldiers as prisoners of war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The dilemma was that tens of thousands of Loyalists were under American control and American retaliation would have been easy.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British built much of their strategy around using these Loyalists.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British maltreated the prisoners whom they held, resulting in more American deaths in the prisons than all the American battlefield mortalities, combined.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] At the end of the war, both sides released their surviving prisoners.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The capture of a British army at Saratoga encouraged the French to formally enter the war in support of Congress, and Benjamin Franklin negotiated a permanent military alliance in early 1778; France thus became the first foreign nation to officially recognize the Declaration of Independence.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On February 6, 1778, the United States and France signed the Treaty of Amity and Commerce and the Treaty of Alliance.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] William Pitt spoke out in Parliament urging Britain to make peace with the Americans and to unite against France, while British politicians who had sympathized with colonial grievances now turned against the Americans for allying with Britain's rival and enemy.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Spanish and the Dutch became allies of the French in 1779 and 1780 respectively, forcing the British to fight a global war without major allies, and requiring it to slip through a combined blockade of the Atlantic.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Dutch Republic, also at war with Britain, was the next country after France to sign a treaty with the United States, on October 8, 1782.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On April 3, 1783, Ambassador Extraordinary Gustaf Philip Creutz, representing King Gustav III of Sweden, and Benjamin Franklin, signed a Treaty of Amity and Commerce with the U.S.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Britain began to view the American Revolutionary War as merely one front in a wider war, and the British chose to withdraw troops from America to reinforce the British colonies in the Caribbean, which were under threat of Spanish or French invasion.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] British commander Sir Henry Clinton evacuated Philadelphia and returned to New York City.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Washington intercepted him in the Battle of Monmouth Court House, the last major battle fought in the north.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] After an inconclusive engagement, the British retreated to New York City.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The northern war subsequently became a stalemate, as the focus of attention shifted to the smaller southern theater.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British Royal Navy blockaded ports and held New York City for the duration of the war, and other cities for brief periods, but failed in their effort to destroy Washington's forces.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British strategy now concentrated on a campaign in the southern states.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Due to a lack of regular troops at their disposal compared to the Americans, the British commanders saw the "southern strategy" as a more viable plan.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] They perceived the Southern Colonies as strongly Loyalist, with a large population of recent British immigrants, and large numbers of slaves who might be tempted to run away from their Patriot masters to join the British and gain their freedom.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Beginning in late December 1778, the British captured Savannah and controlled the Georgia coastline.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In 1780, they launched a fresh invasion and took Charleston.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] A significant victory at the Battle of Camden meant that royal forces soon controlled most of Georgia and South Carolina.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British set up a network of forts inland, hoping that the Loyalists would rally to the flag.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Not enough Loyalists turned out, however, and the British had to fight their way north into North Carolina and Virginia with a severely weakened army.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Behind them, much of the territory that they had already captured dissolved into a chaotic guerrilla war, fought predominantly between bands of Loyalists and American militia, which negated many of the gains that the British had previously made.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British army under Cornwallis marched to Yorktown, Virginia, where they expected to be rescued by a British fleet.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The fleet did arrive, but so did a larger French fleet.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The French were victorious in the Battle of the Chesapeake, and the British fleet returned to New York for reinforcements, leaving Cornwallis trapped.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] In October 1781, the British surrendered their second invading army of the war under a siege by the combined French and Continental armies commanded by Washington.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Washington did not know if or when the British might reopen hostilities after Yorktown.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] They still had 26,000 troops occupying New York City, Charleston, and Savannah, together with a powerful fleet.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The French army and navy departed, so the Americans were on their own in 1782–83.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The American treasury was empty, and the unpaid soldiers were growing restive, almost to the point of mutiny or possible coup d'etat.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Washington dispelled the unrest among officers of the Newburgh Conspiracy in 1783, and Congress subsequently created the promise of a five years bonus for all officers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Historians continue to debate whether the odds were long or short for American victory.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Ferling says that the odds were so long that the American victory was "almost a miracle".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] On the other hand, Joseph Ellis says that the odds favored the Americans, and asks whether there ever was any realistic chance for the British to win.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] He argues that this opportunity came only once, in the summer of 1776, where Admiral Howe and his brother General Howe "missed several opportunities to destroy the Continental Army ....
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Chance, luck, and even the vagaries of the weather played crucial roles." Ellis's point is that the strategic and tactical decisions of the Howes were fatally flawed because they underestimated the challenges posed by the Patriots.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Ellis concludes that, once the Howe brothers failed, the opportunity "would never come again" for a British victory.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Public support for the conflict had never been strong in Britain, where many sympathized with the Americans, but now it reached a new low.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] King George wanted to fight on, but his supporters lost control of Parliament and the British launched no further offensives in America on the eastern seaboard.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] During negotiations in Paris, the American delegation discovered that France supported American independence but no territorial gains, hoping to confine the new nation to the area east of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The Americans opened direct secret negotiations with London, cutting out the French.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] British Prime Minister Lord Shelburne was in charge of the British negotiations, and he saw a chance to make the United States a valuable economic partner, facilitating trade and investment opportunities.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The US obtained all the land east of the Mississippi River, including southern Canada below the Great Lakes, but Spain took control of Florida from the British.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] It gained fishing rights off Canadian coasts, and agreed to allow British merchants and Loyalists to recover their property.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] Prime Minister Shelburne foresaw highly profitable two-way trade between Britain and the rapidly growing United States, which did come to pass.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The blockade was lifted and American merchants were free to trade with any nation anywhere in the world.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] The British largely abandoned their Indigenous allies, who were not a party to this treaty and did not recognize it until they were defeated militarily by the United States.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p01] However, the British did sell them munitions and maintained forts in American territory until the Jay Treaty of 1795.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Britain's war against the Americans, the French, and the Spanish cost about £100 million.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Treasury borrowed 40 percent of the money that it needed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Britain had a sophisticated financial system based on the wealth of thousands of landowners who supported the government, together with banks and financiers in London.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In London the British had relatively little difficulty financing their war, keeping their suppliers and soldiers paid, and hiring tens of thousands of German soldiers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In sharp contrast, Congress and the American states had no end of difficulty financing the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In 1775, there was at most 12 million dollars in gold in the colonies, not nearly enough to cover current transactions, let alone finance a major war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The British made the situation much worse by imposing a tight blockade on every American port, which cut off almost all trade.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] One partial solution was to rely on volunteer support from militiamen and donations from patriotic citizens.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Another was to delay actual payments, pay soldiers and suppliers in depreciated currency, and promise that it would be made good after the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Indeed, the soldiers and officers were given land grants in 1783 to cover the wages that they had earned but had not been paid during the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Starting in 1776, the Congress sought to raise money by loans from wealthy individuals, promising to redeem the bonds after the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The bonds were redeemed in 1791 at face value, but the scheme raised little money because Americans had little specie, and many of the richest merchants were supporters of the Crown.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Beginning in 1777, Congress repeatedly asked the states to provide money, but it had no system of taxation to require funds, and the states were of little help.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] By 1780, Congress was making requisitions for specific supplies of corn, beef, pork, and other necessities, an inefficient system which barely kept the army alive.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Congress used four main methods to cover the cost of the war, which cost about 66 million dollars in specie (gold and silver).
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Significantly, the French secretly supplied the Americans with money, gunpowder, and munitions to weaken Great Britain; the subsidies continued when France entered the war in 1778, and the French government and Paris bankers lent large sums to the American war effort.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Congress also made issues of paper money, known colloquially as "Continental Dollars", in 1775–1780 and in 1780–1781.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The first issue amounted to 242 million dollars.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] This paper money would supposedly be redeemed for state taxes, but the holders were eventually paid off in 1791 at the rate of one cent on the dollar.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] By 1780, the paper money was so devalued that the phrase "not worth a Continental" became synonymous with valueless.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The skyrocketing inflation was a hardship on the few people who had fixed incomes, but 90 percent of the people were farmers and were not directly affected by it.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Debtors benefited by paying off their debts with depreciated paper.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The greatest burden was borne by the soldiers of the Continental Army whose wages were usually paid late and depreciated in value every month, weakening their morale and adding to the hardships of their families.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The national government did not have a strong leader in financial matters until 1781, when Robert Morris was named Superintendent of Finance of the United States.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Morris used a French loan in 1782 to set up the private Bank of North America to finance the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] He reduced the civil list, saved money by using competitive bidding for contracts, tightened accounting procedures, and demanded the national government's full share of money and supplies from the individual states.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The war ended in 1783 and was followed by a period of slow economic recovery that accompanied the end of mercantilism and the resumption and expansion of worldwide trade.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The national government was still operating under the Articles of Confederation and settled the issue of the western territories, which the states ceded to Congress.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] American settlers moved rapidly into those areas, with Vermont, Kentucky, and Tennessee becoming states in the 1790s.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] However, the national government had no authority to tax, no money either to pay the war debts owed to European nations and the private banks, or to pay Americans who had been given millions of dollars of promissory notes for supplies during the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Nationalists led by Washington, Alexander Hamilton, and other veterans feared that the new nation was too fragile to withstand an international war, or even the repetition of internal revolts such as the Shays's Rebellion of 1786 in Massachusetts.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] They convinced the Congress of the Confederation to call the Philadelphia Convention in 1787.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Convention adopted a new Constitution which provided for a republic with authority to tax and a much stronger national government in a federal framework, including an effective executive in a check-and-balance system with the judiciary and legislature.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Constitution was ratified in 1788, after a fierce debate in the states over the proposed new government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The new administration under President George Washington took office in New York in March 1789 and the new bicameral Congress of the United States was seated.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] James Madison spearheaded Congressional legislation proposing amendments to the Constitution as assurances to those cautious about federal power, guaranteeing many of the inalienable rights that formed a foundation for the revolution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Rhode Island was the final state to ratify the Constitution in 1790, the first ten amendments were ratified in 1791 and became known as the United States Bill of Rights.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The national debt fell into three categories after the Revolutionary War.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The first was the $12 million owed to foreigners, mostly money borrowed from France.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] There was general agreement to pay the foreign debts at full value.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The national government owed $40 million and state governments owed $25 million to Americans who had sold food, horses, and supplies to the Patriot forces.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] There were also other debts which consisted of promissory notes issued during the war to soldiers, merchants, and farmers who accepted these payments on the premise that the new nation would create a government that would pay these debts eventually.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Americans struggled to pay off the French loans; they ceased making interest payments to France in 1785 and defaulted on installments due in 1787.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In 1790, however, they resumed regular payments on their debts to the French.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The war expenses of the individual states added up to $114 million, compared to $37 million by the central government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In 1790, Congress combined the remaining state debts with the foreign and domestic debts into one national debt totaling $80 million at the recommendation of first Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Everyone received face value for wartime certificates, so that the national honor would be sustained and the national credit established.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Accounts with the French government were settled in 1795 when James Swan, an American banker acting as agent for France, helped refinance the United States’ remaining debt to France.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The American government issued bonds in the amount of the remaining debt and sold them publicly, with the proceeds going to France through Swan.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The United States no longer owed money to foreign governments, although it continued to owe money to private investors both in the United States and in Europe..
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] This allowed the young United States to place itself on a sound financial footing.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The population of the Thirteen States was not homogeneous in political views and attitudes.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Loyalties and allegiances varied widely within regions and communities and even within families, and sometimes shifted during the Revolution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The American Enlightenment was a critical precursor of the American Revolution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Chief among the ideas of the American Enlightenment were the concepts of natural law, natural rights, consent of the governed, self-determination, equality under the law, liberalism, republicanism, and intolerance of political corruption.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] A growing number of American colonists embraced these views and fostered an intellectual environment which led to a new sense of political and social identity.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] John Locke is often referred to as "the philosopher of the American Revolution" due to his work in the Social Contract and Natural Rights theories that underpinned the Revolution's political ideology.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Locke's *Two Treatises of Government* published in 1689 was especially influential.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] He argued that all humans were created equally free, and governments therefore needed the "consent of the governed".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] This contrasted and conflicted sharply with the British system of inherited political power and hierarchy.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In late eighteenth-century America, belief was still widespread in "equality by creation" and "rights by creation".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Locke's ideas on liberty influenced the political thinking of English writers such as John Trenchard, Thomas Gordon, and Benjamin Hoadly, whose political ideas in turn also had a strong influence on the American Patriots.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] His work also inspired symbols used in the American Revolution such as the "Appeal to Heaven" found on the Pine Tree Flag, which alludes to Locke's concept of the right of revolution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The theory of the social contract influenced the belief among many of the Founders that the right of the people to overthrow their leaders, should those leaders betray the historic rights of Englishmen, was one of the "natural rights" of man.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Americans heavily relied on Montesquieu's analysis of the wisdom of the "balanced" British Constitution (mixed government) in writing the state and national constitutions.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The American interpretation of republicanism was inspired by the Whig party in Great Britain which openly criticized the corruption within the British government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Americans were increasingly embracing republican values, seeing Britain as corrupt and hostile to American interests.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Radical Whig ideology profoundly influenced colonial American political philosophy with its love of liberty and opposition to tyrannical government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The American revolutionaries associated political corruption with ostentatious luxury and inherited aristocracy.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Founding Fathers were strong advocates of republican values, particularly Samuel Adams, Patrick Henry, John Adams, Benjamin Franklin, Thomas Jefferson, Thomas Paine, George Washington, James Madison, and Alexander Hamilton, which required men to put civic duty ahead of their personal desires.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Men were honor bound by civic obligation to be prepared and willing to fight for the rights and liberties of their countrymen.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Protestant churches that had separated from the Church of England, called "dissenters", were the "school of democracy", in the words of historian Patricia Bonomi.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Before the Revolution, the Southern Colonies and three of the New England Colonies had official established churches: Congregational in Massachusetts Bay, Connecticut, and New Hampshire, and the Church of England in Maryland, Virginia, North-Carolina, South Carolina, and Georgia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The colonies of New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Delaware, and the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations had no officially established churches.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] John Witherspoon, who was considered a "new light" Presbyterian, wrote widely circulated sermons linking the American Revolution to the teachings of the Bible.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Throughout the colonies, dissenting Protestant ministers from the Congregational, Baptist, and Presbyterian churches preached Revolutionary themes in their sermons while most Church of England clergymen preached loyalty to the king, the titular head of the English state church.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Religious motivation for fighting tyranny transcended socioeconomic lines.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Historian Bernard Bailyn argues that the evangelicalism of the era challenged traditional notions of natural hierarchy by preaching that the Bible teaches all men are equal, and the true value of a man therefore lies in his moral behavior, not in his class.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Bailyn, on the other hand, denies that religion played such a critical role.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Alan Heimert argues that New Light anti-authoritarianism was essential to furthering democracy in colonial American society, and set the stage for a confrontation with British monarchical and aristocratic rule.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Historians in the early 20th century such as J.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Franklin Jameson examined the class composition of the Patriot cause, looking for evidence of a class war inside the revolution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] More recent historians have largely abandoned that interpretation, emphasizing instead the high level of ideological unity.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Both Loyalists and Patriots were a "mixed lot", but ideological demands always came first.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The revolution became a personal issue for the king, fueled by his growing belief that British leniency would be taken as weakness by the Americans.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] He also sincerely believed that he was defending Britain's constitution against usurpers, rather than opposing patriots fighting for their natural rights.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] King George III is often accused of obstinately trying to keep Great Britain at war with the revolutionaries in America, despite the opinions of his own ministers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Later historians defend George by saying in the context of the times no king would willingly surrender such a large territory, and his conduct was far less ruthless than contemporary monarchs in Europe.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] After the surrender of a British army at Saratoga, both Parliament and the British people were largely in favor of the war; recruitment ran at high levels and although political opponents were vocal, they remained a small minority.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] With the early setbacks in America, Lord North asked to transfer power to Lord Chatham, whom he thought more capable, but George refused to do so; he suggested instead that Chatham serve as a subordinate minister in North's administration, but Chatham refused.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Lord North was allied to the "King's Friends" faction in Parliament and believed George III had the right to exercise extensive powers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In early 1778, Britain's chief rival France signed a treaty of alliance with the United States, and the confrontation soon escalated from a "rebellion" to something that has been characterized as "world war".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The French fleet was able to outrun the British naval blockade of the Mediterranean and sailed to North America.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The conflict now affected North America, Europe and India.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The United States and France were joined by Spain in 1779 and the Dutch Republic, while Britain had no major allies of its own, except for the Loyalist minority in America and German auxiliaries (i.e.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Lord Gower and Lord Weymouth both resigned from the government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Lord North again requested that he also be allowed to resign, but he stayed in office at George III's insistence.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Opposition to the costly war was increasing, and in June 1780 contributed to disturbances in London known as the Gordon riots.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] As late as the Siege of Charleston in 1780, Loyalists could still believe in their eventual victory, as British troops inflicted defeats on the Continental forces at the Battle of Camden and the Battle of Guilford Court House.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In late 1781, the news of Cornwallis's surrender at the siege of Yorktown reached London; Lord North's parliamentary support ebbed away and he resigned the following year.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The king drafted an abdication notice, which was never delivered, finally accepted the defeat in North America, and authorized peace negotiations.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Treaties of Paris, by which Britain recognized the sovereignty of the United States and returned Florida to Spain, were signed in 1782 and 1783 respectively.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In early 1783, George III privately conceded "America is lost!" He reflected that the former colonies had developed into Britain's "successful rivals" in commercial trade and fishing as the United States.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] When John Adams was appointed American Minister to London in 1785, George had become resigned to the new relationship between his country and the former colonies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Those who fought for independence were called "Revolutionaries", "Continentals", "Rebels", "Patriots", "Whigs", "Congress-men", or "Americans" during and after the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] They included a full range of social and economic classes but were unanimous regarding the need to defend the natural rights of Americans and uphold the principles of republicanism in rejecting monarchy and aristocracy, while emphasizing civic virtue by citizens.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The signers of the Declaration of Independence were overwhelmingly—with definite exceptions—well-educated, of British stock, and of the Protestant faith.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Newspapers were strongholds of patriotism (although there were a few Loyalist papers) and printed many pamphlets, announcements, patriotic letters, and pronouncements.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] According to historian Robert Calhoon, 40 to 45 percent of the white population in the Thirteen Colonies supported the Patriots' cause, 15 to 20 percent supported the Loyalists, and the remainder were neutral or kept a low profile.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Mark Lender concludes that ordinary people became insurgents against the British because they held a sense of rights which the British were violating, rights that stressed local autonomy, fair dealing, and government by consent.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] They were highly sensitive to the issue of tyranny, which they saw manifested in the British response to the Boston Tea Party.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The arrival in Boston of the British Army heightened their sense of violated rights, leading to rage and demands for revenge.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] They had faith that God was on their side.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Patriots viewed independence as a means to gain freedom from British oppression and initially to reassert their rights on par with subjects in Britain.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Most yeomen farmers, craftsmen, and small merchants joined the Patriot cause to demand more political equality.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] They were especially successful in Pennsylvania but less so in New England, where John Adams attacked Thomas Paine's *Common Sense* for the "absurd democratical notions" that it proposed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Thomas Paine published his pamphlet *Common Sense* in January 1776, after the Revolution had started.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] It was widely distributed and often read aloud in taverns, contributing significantly to concurrently spreading the ideas of republicanism and liberalism, bolstering enthusiasm for separation from Great Britain, and encouraging recruitment for the Continental Army.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Paine presented the Revolution as the solution for Americans alarmed by the threat of tyranny.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The consensus of scholars is that about 15 to 20 percent of the white population remained loyal to the British Crown.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Those who actively supported the king were known at the time as "Loyalists", "Tories", or "King's men".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Loyalists never controlled territory unless the British Army occupied it.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] They were typically older, less willing to break with old loyalties, and often connected to the Church of England; they included many established merchants with strong business connections throughout the Empire, as well as royal officials such as Thomas Hutchinson of Boston.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In the mid-20th century, historian Leonard Woods Labaree identified eight characteristics of the Loyalists that made them essentially conservative, opposite to the characteristics of the Patriots.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists tended to feel that resistance to the Crown was morally wrong, while the Patriots thought that morality was on their side.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists were alienated when the Patriots resorted to violence, such as burning houses and tarring and feathering.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Many Loyalists wanted to take a centrist position and resisted the Patriots' demand to declare their opposition to the Crown.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Numerous Loyalists had maintained strong and long-standing relations with Britain, especially merchants in port cities such as New York and Boston.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Many Loyalists felt that independence was bound to come eventually, but they were fearful that revolution might lead to anarchy, tyranny, or mob rule.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In contrast, the prevailing attitude among Patriots was a desire to seize the initiative.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Labaree also contended that Loyalists were pessimists who lacked the confidence in the future displayed by the Patriots.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] There were "tens of thousands" of Black Loyalists, enslaved African Americans who escaped to British lines and supported Britain's cause via several means.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Many of them died from disease, but the survivors were evacuated by the British to their remaining colonies in North America.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The revolution could divide families, such as William Franklin, son of Benjamin Franklin and royal governor of the Province of New Jersey who remained loyal to the Crown throughout the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Recent immigrants who had not been fully Americanized were also inclined to support the King.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] After the war, the great majority of the half-million Loyalists remained in America and resumed normal lives.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Some became prominent American leaders, such as Samuel Seabury.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Approximately 46,000 Loyalists relocated to Canada; others moved to Britain (7,000), Florida, or the West Indies (9,000).
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The exiles represented approximately two percent of the total population of the colonies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Nearly all Black Loyalists left for Nova Scotia, Florida, or England, where they could remain free.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists who left the South in 1783 took thousands of enslaved persons with them as they fled to the British West Indies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] A minority of uncertain size tried to stay neutral in the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Most kept a low profile, but the Quakers were the most important group to speak out for neutrality, especially in Pennsylvania.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Quakers continued to do business with the British even after the war began, and they were accused of supporting British rule, "contrivers and authors of seditious publications" critical of the revolutionary cause.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Most Quakers remained neutral, although a sizeable number participated to some degree.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Women contributed to the American Revolution in many ways and were involved on both sides.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Formal politics did not include women, but ordinary domestic behaviors became charged with political significance as Patriot women confronted a war which permeated all aspects of political, civil, and domestic life.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] They participated by boycotting British goods, spying on the British, following armies as they marched, washing, cooking, and mending for soldiers, delivering secret messages, and even fighting disguised as men in a few cases, such as Deborah Samson.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Mercy Otis Warren held meetings in her house and cleverly attacked Loyalists with her creative plays and histories.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Many women also acted as nurses and helpers, tending to the soldiers' wounds and buying and selling goods for them.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Some of these camp followers even participated in combat, such as Madam John Turchin who led her husband's regiment into battle.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Above all, women continued the agricultural work at home to feed their families and the armies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] They maintained their families during their husbands' absences and sometimes after their deaths.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] American women were integral to the success of the boycott of British goods, as the boycotted items were largely household articles such as tea and cloth.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Women had to return to knitting goods and to spinning and weaving their own cloth—skills that had fallen into disuse.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In 1769, the women of Boston produced 40,000 skeins of yarn, and 180 women in Middletown, Massachusetts wove 20,522 yards (18,765 m) of cloth.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Many women gathered food, money, clothes, and other supplies during the war to help the soldiers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] A woman's loyalty to her husband could become an open political act, especially for women in America committed to men who remained loyal to the King.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Legal divorce, usually rare, was granted to Patriot women whose husbands supported the King.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In early 1776, France set up a major program of aid to the Americans, and the Spanish secretly added funds.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Each country spent one million "livres tournaises" to buy munitions.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] A dummy corporation run by Pierre Beaumarchais concealed their activities.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] American Patriots obtained some munitions from the Dutch Republic as well, through the French and Spanish ports in the West Indies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Heavy expenditures and a weak taxation system pushed France toward bankruptcy.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In 1777, Charles François Adrien le Paulmier, Chevalier d'Annemours, acting as a secret agent for France, made sure General George Washington was privy to his mission.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] He followed Congress around for the next two years, reporting what he observed back to France.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Treaty of Alliance between the French and the Americans followed in 1778, which led to more French money, matériel and troops being sent to the United States.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Spain did not officially recognize the United States, but it was a French ally and it separately declared war on Britain on June 21, 1779.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Bernardo de Gálvez, general of the Spanish forces in New Spain bordering the Americans, also served as governor of Louisiana.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] He led an expedition of colonial troops to capture Florida from the British and to keep open a vital conduit for supplies going to the Americans.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Ethnic Germans served on both sides of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] As George III was also the Elector of Hanover, many supported the Loyalist cause and served as allies of the Kingdom of Great Britain; most notably rented auxiliary troops from German states such as the Landgraviate of Hessen-Kassel.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] American Patriots tended to represent such troops as mercenaries in propaganda against the British Crown.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Even American historians followed suit, in spite of Colonial-era jurists drawing a distinction between auxiliaries and mercenaries, with auxiliaries serving their prince when sent to the aid of another prince, and mercenaries serving a foreign prince as individuals.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] By this distinction the troops which served in the American Revolution were auxiliaries.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Other German individuals came to assist the American revolutionaries, most notably Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben, who served as a general in the Continental Army and is credited with professionalizing that force, but most Germans who served were already colonists.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Von Steuben's native Prussia joined the League of Armed Neutrality, and King Frederick II of Prussia was well appreciated in the United States for his support early in the war.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] He expressed interest in opening trade with the United States and bypassing English ports, and allowed an American agent to buy arms in Prussia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Frederick predicted American success, and promised to recognize the United States and American diplomats once France did the same.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Prussia also interfered in the recruiting efforts of Russia and neighboring German states when they raised armies to send to the Americas, and Frederick II forbade enlistment for the American war within Prussia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] All Prussian roads were denied to troops from Anhalt-Zerbst, which delayed reinforcements that Howe had hoped to receive during the winter of 1777–1778.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] However, when the War of the Bavarian Succession (1778–1779) erupted, Frederick II became much more cautious with Prussian/British relations.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] U.S. ships were denied access to Prussian ports, and Frederick refused to officially recognize the United States until they had signed the Treaty of Paris.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Even after the war, Frederick II predicted that the United States was too large to operate as a republic, and that it would soon rejoin the British Empire with representatives in Parliament.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Most Indigenous people rejected pleas that they remain neutral and instead supported the British Crown.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The great majority of the ~200,000 indigenous people east of the Mississippi distrusted the Americans and supported the British cause, hoping to forestall continued expansion of settlement into their territories.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Those tribes closely involved in trade tended to side with the Patriots, although political factors were important as well.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Some tried to remain neutral, seeing little value in joining what they perceived to be a "white man's war", and fearing reprisals from whichever side they opposed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The British did have other indigenous allies, particularly in the regions of southwest Quebec on the Patriot's frontier.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The British provided arms to Indigenous people who were led by Loyalists in war parties to raid frontier settlements from the Carolinas to New York.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] These war parties killed many settlers on the frontier, especially in western Pennsylvania and New York's Mohawk Valley.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In 1776, Cherokee war parties attacked American settlers all along the southern Quebec frontier of the uplands throughout the Washington District, North Carolina (now Tennessee) and the Kentucky wilderness area.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Chickamauga Cherokee under Tsiyu Gansini (*also* Dragging Canoe) allied themselves closely with the British, and fought on for an additional decade after the Treaty of Paris was signed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] They launched raids with roughly 200 warriors, as seen in the Cherokee–American wars; they could not mobilize enough forces to invade settler areas without the help of allies, most often the Creek.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Joseph Brant (*also* Thayendanegea), from the powerful Mohawk tribe of the Haudenosaunee Confederacy, was the most prominent Indigenous leader against the Patriot forces.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In 1778 and 1780, he led 300 Iroquois warriors and 100 white Loyalists in multiple attacks on small frontier settlements in New York and Pennsylvania, killing many settlers and destroying villages, crops, and food stockpiles.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In 1779, the Continental Army forced the hostile Indigenous people out of upstate New York when Washington sent an army under John Sullivan which destroyed 40 evacuated Iroquois villages in central and western New York.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The Battle of Newtown proved decisive, as the Patriots had an advantage of three-to-one, and it ended significant resistance; there was little combat otherwise.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Facing starvation and homeless for the winter, the Iroquois that allied with the British fled to Canada.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] At the peace conference following the war, the British ceded lands which they did not really control, without consultation with their Indigenous allies that inhabited them.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] They transferred control to the United States of all the land south of the Great Lakes east of the Mississippi and north of Florida.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The existence of slavery in the American colonies had attracted criticism from both sides of the Atlantic as many could not reconcile the existence of the institution with the egalitarian ideals espoused by leaders of the Revolution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The English writer Samuel Johnson wrote "how is it we hear the loudest yelps for liberty among the drivers of the Negroes?" in a text opposing the grievances of the colonists.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Crispus Attucks, of mixed racial heritage, was one of the five people killed in the Boston Massacre in 1770 and is considered the first American casualty for the cause of independence.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Free Blacks in the New England Colonies and Middle Colonies in the North as well as Southern Colonies fought on both sides of the War, but the majority fought for the Patriots.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Gary Nash reports that there were about 9,000 Black veteran Patriots, counting the Continental Army and Navy, state militia units, privateers, wagoneers in the Army, servants to officers, and spies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The effects of the war were more dramatic in the South.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Tens of thousands of enslaved persons escaped to British lines throughout the South, causing dramatic losses to slaveholders and disrupting cultivation and harvesting of crops.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] For instance, South Carolina was estimated to have lost about 25,000 enslaved persons to flight, migration, or death which amounted to a third of its enslaved population.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] As noted by the historian Karen Cook Bell, during the Revolutionary War roughly one-third of all the escaped enslaved were women, even though prior to 1775 nearly 87% had been men.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] During the war, British commanders attempted to weaken the Patriots by issuing proclamations of freedom to their enslaved.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] In the November 1775 document known as Dunmore's Proclamation Virginia royal governor, Lord Dunmore recruited Black men for British military service with the promise of freedom, protection for their families, and land grants.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Hundreds of Black men responded and were formed into the Royal Ethiopian Regiment.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Colonists, primarily Southern Patriots, were deeply angered by Dunmore's proclamation, which spread through all of the Thirteen Colonies and threatened to upturn the existing American racial hierarchy; it also played a major role in Southern support for American independence.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Accusations that the British were encouraging slave rebellions were prominent features of Patriot propaganda, with Jefferson even accusing George III in the 27 colonial grievances of having "excited domestic Insurrections among us".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] The 1779 Philipsburg Proclamation expanded the promise of freedom for Black men who enlisted in the British military to all the colonies in rebellion.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] At the conclusion of the war, British forces gave transportation to 10,000 of the formerly enslaved when they evacuated Savannah and Charles Town, carrying through on their promise.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] They evacuated and resettled more than 3,000 Black Loyalists from New York to Nova Scotia, Upper Canada, and Lower Canada.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Others sailed with the British to England or were resettled as freedmen in the West Indies of the Caribbean.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] But the enslaved carried to the Caribbean under control of Loyalist masters generally remained enslaved until the British abolition of slavery in its colonies in 1833–1838.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] More than 1,200 of the Black Loyalists of Nova Scotia later resettled in the British colony of Sierra Leone in Africa, where they became leaders of the Krio ethnic group of Freetown and the later national government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Many of their descendants still live in Sierra Leone, as well as other African countries.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Despite the turmoil of the period, African-Americans contributed to the foundation of an American national identity during the Revolution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p02] Phyllis Wheatley, an African American poet, popularized the image of Columbia to represent America.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] After the Revolution, genuinely democratic politics became possible in the former American colonies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The rights of the people were incorporated into state constitutions.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Concepts of liberty, consent of the governed, individual rights, equality and due process under the law, and intolerance of corruption became incorporated as core values of liberal republicanism.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The new United States government was empowered to undertake its own project of territorial expansion and settler colonialism.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The greatest challenge to the old order in Europe was the challenge to inherited political power and the democratic idea that government rests on the consent of the governed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Losing the war and the Thirteen Colonies was a shock to Britain.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The war revealed the limitations of Britain's fiscal-military state when they discovered that they suddenly faced powerful enemies with no allies, and they were dependent on extended and vulnerable transatlantic lines of communication.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The defeat heightened dissension and escalated political antagonism to the king's ministers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The king went so far as to draft letters of abdication, although they were never delivered.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Inside Parliament, the primary concern changed from fears of an over-mighty monarch to the issues of representation, parliamentary reform, and government retrenchment.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Unable to accept loss of the war and the colonies as possibly due to anything else but widespread institutional corruption, reformers sought to root it out, and the result was a crisis from 1776 to 1783.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The crisis ended after 1784 confidence in the British constitution was restored during the administration of Prime Minister William Pitt.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution ended an age—an age of monarchy.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] And, it began a new age—an age of freedom.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] As a result of the growing wave started by the Revolution, there are now more people around the world living in freedom than ever before, both in absolute numbers and as a percentage of the world's population.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Interpretations vary concerning the effect of the Revolution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Historians such as Bernard Bailyn, Gordon Wood, and Edmund Morgan view it as a unique and radical event which produced deep changes and had a profound effect on world affairs, such as an increasing belief in the principles of the Enlightenment.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] These were demonstrated by a leadership and government that espoused protection of natural rights, and a system of laws chosen by the people.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] John Murrin, by contrast, argues that the definition of "the people" at that time was mostly restricted to free men who passed a property qualification.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The first shot of the American Revolution at the Battle of Lexington and Concord is referred to as the "shot heard 'round the world".
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution was the first of the Atlantic Revolutions: followed most notably by the French Revolution, the Haitian Revolution, and the Latin American wars of independence.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Aftershocks contributed to rebellions in Ireland, the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, and the Netherlands.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Constitution, drafted shortly after independence, remains the world's oldest written constitution, and has been emulated by other countries, in some cases verbatim.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Some historians and scholars argue that the subsequent wave of independence and revolutionary movements has contributed to the continued expansion of democratic government; 144 countries, representing two-third of the world's population, are full or partially democracies of some form.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The Revolution had a strong, immediate influence in Great Britain, Ireland, the Netherlands, and France.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Many British and Irish Whigs in Parliament spoke glowingly in favor of the American cause.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] In Ireland, the Protestant minority who controlled Ireland demanded self-rule.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Under the leadership of Henry Grattan, the Irish Patriot Party forced the reversal of mercantilist prohibitions against trade with other British colonies.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The King and his cabinet in London could not risk another rebellion, and so made a series of concessions to the Patriot faction in Dublin.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Armed volunteer units of the *Protestant Ascendancy* were set up ostensibly to protect against an invasion from France.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] As had been in colonial America, so too in Ireland now the King no longer had a monopoly of lethal force.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] By 1798, the Irish were ready for a republican uprising.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] For many Europeans, such as the Marquis de Lafayette, who later were active during the era of the French Revolution, the American case along with the Dutch Revolt (end of the 16th century) and the 17th century English Civil War, was among the examples of overthrowing an old regime.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The American Declaration of Independence influenced the French Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen of 1789.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The spirit of the Declaration of Independence led to laws ending slavery in all the Northern states and the Northwest Territory, with New Jersey the last in 1804.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] States such as New Jersey and New York adopted gradual emancipation, which kept some people as slaves for more than two decades longer.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] During the revolution, the contradiction between the Patriots' professed ideals of liberty and the institution of slavery generated increased scrutiny of the latter.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] As early as 1764, the Boston Patriot leader James Otis, Jr. declared that all men, "white or black", were "by the law of nature" born free.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Anti-slavery calls became more common in the early 1770s.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] In 1773, Benjamin Rush, the future signer of the Declaration of Independence, called on "advocates for American liberty" to oppose slavery.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Slavery became an issue that had to be addressed.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] In the late 1760s and early 1770s, several colonies, including Massachusetts and Virginia, attempted to restrict the slave trade, but were prevented from doing so by royally appointed governors.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] In 1774, as part of a broader non-importation movement aimed at Britain, the Continental Congress called on all the colonies to ban the importation of enslaved people, and the colonies passed acts doing so.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] In the first two decades after the American Revolution, state legislatures and individuals took actions to free the enslaved, in part based on Revolutionary ideals.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Northern states passed new constitutions that contained language about equal rights or specifically abolished slavery; some states, such as New York and New Jersey, where slavery was more widespread, passed laws by the end of the 18th century to abolish slavery by a gradual method.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] By 1804, all the northern states had passed laws outlawing slavery, either immediately or over time.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] However, enslavers could grant freedom to individuals they enslaved.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Numerous slaveholders who freed their enslaved cited Revolutionary ideals in their documents; others freed their enslaved as a reward for service.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Records also suggest that some slaveholders were freeing their own mixed-race children, born to enslaved mothers.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The number of free Blacks as a proportion of the Black population in the upper South increased from less than 1 percent to nearly 10 percent between 1790 and 1810 as a result of these actions.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Nevertheless, slavery continued in the South, where it was protected as a "peculiar institution", setting the stage for future sectional conflict between North and South over the issue.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Thousands of free Blacks in the northern states fought in the state militias and Continental Army.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] In the south, both sides offered freedom to slaves who would perform military service.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Roughly 20,000 enslaved persons fought in the American Revolution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] While women were entering a period in which they found themselves gaining more identity within society, it was clear that they were still very much considered under men as their role in society remained being a good wife and mother.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Having a woman who was dressed well for her role as a good wife and mother as well as fitting the social role, was a symbol of not only status, but a family devoted to the republic.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] As they continued to nurture social and political partnerships, their role in enabling the success of the revolution emphasized their changing role in society – leading to the post-revolutionary reconstruction of gender ideology.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] In addition, the democratic ideals of the Revolution inspired changes in the roles of women.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Patriot women married to Loyalists who left the state could get a divorce and obtain control of the ex-husband's property.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] As discussions rose regarding the rights of man post Revolutionary war, women began pushing a debate for the rights of women as well.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Mary Wollstonecraft pioneered the discussion regarding women's rights, and push those like Abigail Adams to begin expressing the desire to want a larger place in society.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Wollstonecraft was an English writer, philosopher, and advocate for women's rights, and would publish the *Vindication of the Rights of Woman* (1792) – challenging the idea that rights should only be granted to men.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Her radical ideas would give ground to the conversation in allowing women to be bearers of rights alongside men – that while the rights of man were taking on a new meaning post-revolutionary America, it was time for the rights of women too.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Inspired by the radical feminism in her work, women in the early republic would change their views on marriage, education, participation in public life, and autonomy – pushing them to lay the groundwork for the later women's suffrage movement, education opportunities, property rights, and more.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] However, this new sense of independence and dignity did not come with ease, as a gender hierarchy would continue to bind what it meant for women to have rights during the post-revolutionary era.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Women in the early republic had many limitations – they could not vote, hold political office, earn fair wages, lacked opportunities for higher education and certain professions, and most importantly, own property independently of their husbands.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] In addition, they held little legal powers in subjects such as divorce, property rights, and child custody.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] A central legal concept that reinforced these restrictions was *coverture*, a central legal doctrine that limited women's lives in all aspects – making a woman's legal identity a part of their husband's.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The early national period of America would continue to struggle with the concept of rights and equality.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Tens of thousands of Loyalists left the United States following the war; Philip Ranlet estimates 20,000, while Maya Jasanoff estimates as many as 70,000.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Some migrated to Britain, but the great majority received land and subsidies for resettlement in British colonies in North America, especially Quebec (concentrating in the Eastern Townships), Prince Edward Island, and Nova Scotia.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Britain created the colonies of Upper Canada (Ontario) and New Brunswick expressly for their benefit, and the Crown awarded land to Loyalists as compensation for losses in the United States.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Nevertheless, approximately eighty-five percent of the Loyalists stayed in the United States as American citizens, and some of the exiles later returned to the U.S.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Patrick Henry spoke of the issue of allowing Loyalists to return as such: "Shall we, who have laid the proud British lion at our feet, be frightened of its whelps?" His actions helped secure return of the Loyalists to American soil.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution has a central place in the American memory as the story of the nation's founding.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] It is covered in the schools, memorialized by two national holidays, Washington's Birthday in February and Independence Day in July, and commemorated in innumerable monuments.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] George Washington's estate at Mount Vernon was one of the first national pilgrimages for tourists and attracted 10,000 visitors a year by the 1850s.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The Revolution became a matter of contention in the 1850s in the debates leading to the American Civil War (1861–1865), as spokesmen of both the Northern United States and the Southern United States claimed that their region was the true custodian of the legacy of 1776.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The United States Bicentennial in 1976 came a year after the American withdrawal from the Vietnam War, and speakers stressed the themes of renewal and rebirth based on a restoration of traditional values.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] Today, more than 100 battlefields and historic sites of the American Revolution are protected and maintained by the government.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/american-revolution-p03] The National Park Service alone manages and maintains more than 50 battlefield parks and many other sites such as Independence Hall that are related to the Revolution.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/thomas-nelson-jr] Nelson was the grandson of Thomas "Scotch Tom" Nelson, an immigrant son of a cloth merchant from Penrith in Cumberland, England, who after three voyages to the Virginia colony settled at and developed Yorktown, where the York River drained into Mobjack Bay.
[src:thomas-nelson-jr/thomas-nelson-jr] During the following three decades, Scotch Tom not only increased his wealth, but parlayed it into influence so that his children (and grandchildren) married into the First Families of Virginia.
